deck_excerpt: Turn your opponent's graveyard into your own personal Extra Deck
deck_description:
The goal of Zombie World is to use the Field Spell of the same name to turn your opponents GY into a 2nd extra deck for you to pull from. Most of the monsters here can hold their own even if Zombie World isn't present, so you can use your Extra Deck to wreak havoc while you wait for it. Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring: A Level 3 Tuner that also doubles as a hand trap which can be used to prevent the opponent from pulling cards directly from their deck. Doomking Balerdroch: A Level 8 monster that can easily be Special Summoned from the Graveyard by it's own effect, Book Of Life, Call Of The Haunted, or from the deck by Pyramid Turtle's effect. Tribute Summoning isn't recommended, as the other methods are easier and keep your monster's alive. Pyramid Turtle's effect is the most useful method, and this monsters ATK is often worth sacrificing the turtle during your own Battle Phase, especially early on in the duel. Not only is this monster powerful, but it can activate either of it's effect's once per turn when another Zombie on the field activates an effect of it's own. This opens up more opportunities if Zombie World is active, allowing you to either negate an effect, or Banish any monster on the field or in the Graveyard. Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion: A Level 3 Tuner that also doubles as a hand trap which can be used to prevent the opponent from moving cards around from their Graveyard. Necroworld Banshee: While she is on the field, your Zombie World is protected from being destroyed or negated. You can also banish her at any time to immediately activate another Zombie World from your deck or hand. Paladin Of The Cursed Dragon: This guy lets you Special Summon 1 Zombie monster from your opponent's GY that was destroyed by battle. Pyramid Turtle: This is the most efficient Zombie searcher I'm aware of. Truly an amazing card. Literally every monster in the Main deck can be Special Summoned via it's effect once destroyed. This is an easy way to get quickly get Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon or Doomking Balerdroch onto the field. Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon. Despite being Level 7, as long as you have a Zombie monster, (which is your entire deck), it can be Tributed using only 1 Tribute. Any Zombie monster this monster destroys can be Special Summoned to your side of the field as soon as it has been sent to the GY. Scapeghost: A good defensive tool if you are being overwhelmed. The maximum amount of Tokens it creates with it's flip effect can be used to perform up to 2 Link Summons, or up to 2 Fusion Summons, provided you have a Polymerization ready. Scapeghost itself is also a Tuner, and if you flip it yourself and have at least a Level 4 monster ready, you can use 2 of the Tokens, Scapeghost, and the Level 4 monster to Synchro Summon one of the most powerful monsters in the deck, Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon. Doing the same thing but using all 3 of the tokens instead will allow you to Synchro Summon Shiranui Shogunsaga. Zombie Master: By sending 1 monster from your hand to your GY, you can Special Summon any Zombie monster from either GY that is Level 4 or lower. An incredibly easy way to set up an XYZ Summon for Gem-Knight Pearl, or a Synchro Summon for Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon. Book Of Life: Revives 1 of your monsters from the GY and banishes one of your opponent's monsters from their GY. Essentially a Monster Reborn that can also hinder your opponent. Polymerization: Used to Fusion Summon Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon or Starving Venom Fusion Dragon. Super Polymerization: A quick-play version of Polymerization that can't be negated. It uses monsters on either side of the field, meaning you can use your opponents transformed Zombies to summon one of 2 powerful Dragons with manipulative effects. Be mindful that Super Polymerization does not work with materials in the hand the same way normal Polymerization does. Terraforming: Instant access to Zombie World. Zombie World: The most important card in the deck, this Field Spell not only transforms all monsters on both fields and GY's into Zombie-types, it also prevents both players from Tribute Summoning any monster that isn't a Zombie. Luckily for you, everything at your disposal is already a Zombie. This card not only hinders your opponent, but it basically turns Paladin Of The Cursed Dragon and Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon into the apocalypse, stealing monsters from the opponent's GY and turning them against them. Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon absolutely loves this card and benefits immensely from it. Call Of The Haunted: Revives 1 monster from your GY. Dust Tornado: Destroys 1 of your opponents Spells/Traps. Mirror Force: Upon declaring an attack, your opponent's attack position monsters are destroyed. Seven Tools Of The Bandit: Negates a single Trap card's activation. Trap Of The Imperial Tomb: When a Zombie is summoned from your opponent's GY to your field, you can destroy 2 cards on the field. Makes a great combo when either Paladin Of The Cursed Dragon, Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon, or Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon's summoning effect is activated. Tutan Mask: Protects a single Zombie from a Spell or Trap. Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon: [2 Zombie monsters] By fusing any 2 Zombie monsters, you have a behemoth of a monster that can create clones of the monster it battles. Even though this monster can't destroy monsters by battle, anything it attacks (or is attacked by) has it's ATK reduced to 0, and you spawn a Token gifted with the attacked monsters original ATK and Level (as long as that target has a level). Be mindful that Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon can be destroyed by battle if the attacking monster overpowers it, but not before creating a token. After a Token has outlived it's usefulness, it can be used as a Tribute Summon for Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon, Synchro Material, or even Link Materials for Vampire Sucker. Starving Venom Fusion Dragon: Relatively easy to summon, requiring any 2 DARK monsters aside from tokens, Starving Venom Fusion Dragon gains ATK equal to one of your opponents Special Summoned monsters the turn it is Fusion Summoned. It can also copy the effects of a single Level 5 or higher monster that your opponent controls once per turn. This is deadly and can be abused when combined with the Summoning effects of Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon, Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon, and Vampire Sucker. Lastly, when this monster is destroyed, your opponents loses all of the Special Summoned monsters they have on the field. Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon: [1 Tuner + 1 or more non-Tuner monsters] By far the most powerful monster in the entire deck. Starting off with 2400 ATK, it gains an additional 100 ATK for each Zombie on the field and in both GY's. If Zombie World is active and the GY's are packed, this monster's ATK can reach insanely high levels. Not only that, but anytime a Zombie is destroyed by battle, this monster's effect activates and lets you Special Summon ANY Zombie monster from either GY. Shiranui Shogunsaga: When this card is Special Summoned, you can banish 1 Zombie from your Graveyard to have this card gain ATK equal to the sent monsters ATK for 1 turn. When combined with Zombie World, this could potentially give this monster a grand total of 7500 ATK depending on what you choose. Since it's effect activates upon being Special Summoned, you can use Book Of Life and Call Of The Haunted once it's been sent to the Graveyard to retaliate when your opponent controls a powerful monster. Gem-Knight Pearl: [2 level 4 monsters] A powerful, easy to summon 2600 attacker, only lacking an effect. Number 22: Zombiestein: 2 Level 8 DARK monsters. You can use any combination of 2 Doomking Balerdroch, Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon, or Starving Venom Fusion Dragon to XYZ Summon this titan. Without protection, this monster's effect negation isn't too useful; it's insanely high ATK is what gives it a spot in this deck. If it somehow makes it into the Graveyard, it can be used to give Shiranui Shogunsaga an absurd boost in power. Vampire Sucker: [2 Zombie monsters] This monsters effect might not seem too helpful, but you can create a few combos with it. Once per turn, you can summon any monster from your opponent's GY to their side of the field in DEF position, and turn it into a Zombie (useful for instances when Zombie World is not active). That monster can then be used in one of 2 ways. It can be used as a Tribute for a Tribute summon (Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon) even though you don't control them, it can also be used to create a Token for Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon. Further more, summoning the monster let's you draw a card. Of course, her draw effect can be triggered any time a Zombie monster is Special Summoned.

Feel free to share any ideas/strategies that you think might work better and I'll look into them. ~~~Special thanks to YGOPRODECK user "Ashvenfall" for reminding me that Super Polymerization is a thing and introducing me to Doomking Balerdroch. I have tested these cards and they have increased the efficiency of the deck by a considerable amount.~~~

deck_excerpt: An Aromage Deck featuring the KICO Rose Cards.
deck_description: "The Aromatherapists work in a unique garden. Fragrant Scents fill the air as they work. Seeming to have effects that are magical in nature. some had posited that it has to do with the small fairy living in the garden. Regardless of the mysterious nature, these scents had led them to be known as 'Aromages'. The gardeners here are a family of 6. Bergamot and Majoram are the parent,s while Jasmine, Rosemary, Laurel and Canaga are their daughters and Sons. They are aided by Angelica, a fairy of unique magic. Angelica had recently shown the ability to make the gardeners more like themself, empowering those that allow Angelica to bless them a new form." By all accounts this is pretty standard. Aroma are a Synchro and LP focused deck and as thus I have added cards that help with Synchro summoning or LP (or both) The general playmakers would be  Jasmine, Angelica and Laurel. Jasmine, in adition to being adorable, works to get you a second Normal Summon and a draw. Laurel and Angelica meanwhile have ways to Summon themselves and allow access to Synchro plays. Of the other four, Rosemary works to put monsters in defense, Canaga bounces spells, Majoram banishes form the GY and Bergamot is basically the main deck boss. The women also have ED versions of themselves, enhanced by Angelina's power. Jasmine's is a better playmaker that works for all Plant Decks, Rosemary's buffs the ATK of your board and negates effects and Majoram's searches some importaint Traps. The traps in question are Humid Winds, Dried Winds and Blessed Winds. Of course I only run the former and latter. Humid lets you search a mage, and Blessed serves as a way to get LP or summon an Aroma monster form the GY. The spells are also pretty important. Aroma Garden being a field that grants consistent LP and an atk buff to go with Rosemary's, and Aroma Gardening does the same but also lets you get a monster form the deck if you happen to be losing. Off theme support includes Spore, Rose Princess, White Rose Cloister, Rose Fairy, and Staysailor Romarin. I also run Gingerbread House as a tech for more LP and possible popping of their monsters or making Rosemary's negate a quick effect, Juragedo as a free body that also gets LP and One for One and Super Solar Nutrient for more summoning form the deck. The Extra Deck, besides the Aromaseraphy monsters, also has the game-breaking Crystron Halqifibrax, as well as Desert Locusts, Trishula, Linkuriboh, Black Rose Dragon, Crossrose Dragon, Ancient Sacred Wyvern, Dawn Dragster, Barricadeborg Blocker, Saryuja Skull Dread, and...that's about it For the side I actually have 4 open slots so Efect Veiler and Twin Twisters are placeholders. The actual side deck has Red Resonator, Ghost Sister and Spooky Dogwood, Dinowrestler Pankratops, Rose Lover and a 3rd copy of Gardening and Blessed Winds. This is my Aromage deck, as per usual I appreciate some feedback (though I will preface this by saying that I will eventually acquire Dried Winds.)

deck_excerpt: Flip-Summoning monsters has never been so much fun...
deck_description: Originally based on the old Structure Deck "Invincible Fortress", this setup is geared more towards Flip-Summon effects, rather than defensive damage. Most of the monsters from Invincible Fortress are present here and retain their high defenses, they just operate with a different overall play style than before. The main theme of the deck is utilizing Rock monster Flip-Summoning to place your opponent's monsters back into their hand, paving the way for multiple direct attacks. What makes this much easier, is that the majority of the monsters here all share the same effect of: "Once per turn: You can change this card to face-down Defense Position". MAIN DECK Each monster that can be flipped face-down once per turn activate the following effects when they are Flip-Summoned: Golem Sentry - Returns 1 of your opponent's monsters to their hand. Guardian Sphinx - Returns all of your opponent's monsters to their hand (requires 1 Tribute to summon). Pharaonic Guardian Sphinx - Shuffles all monsters your opponent controls back into the deck (requires 2 Tributes to summon). Medusa Worm - Destroys 1 monster your opponent controls. Des Lacooda - You draw 1 card. Moai Interceptor Cannons - Can be flipped face down, but does not have a secondary effect. There are also various ways to protect your monsters. Controlling Hieracosphinx prevents your opponent from attacking your face down monsters, while Swords Of Revealing Light prevents all attacks against you for 3 turns. Catapult Zone can be used to protect your important monsters while sending high level monsters to the GY for easy Special Summoning via The Shallow Grave, and Call Of The Haunted (be mindful that The Shallow Grave also works for your opponent). Terraforming and Metaverse provide easy access to Catapult Zone. Other high level monsters include Criosphinx and Exxod, Master Of The Guard. Criosphinx synergizes well with Golem Sentry, Guardian Sphinx, and Ordeal Of A Traveler. These cards return other cards to the hand, and each time a monster is returned to the opponent's hand, Criosphinx causes your opponent to randomly discard 1 card. This can be done multiple times per turn. Exxod, Master Of The Guard combos effectively with any monster that can be flipped face down. Sporting 4000 DEF, he acts as a wall that burns the opponent for 1000 damage each time an EARTH monster is Flip-Summoned, (which is the entire deck lol) although Tributing a Sphinx monster is required to Special Summon him. The effects of Golem Sentry and/or either Sphinx monster can really hurt the opponent, and leave an opening for them to finish off the remainder of Life Points. The final monster is Des Lacooda, who can also be flipped face down once per turn. This creepy looking guy is a draw engine and the only monster who can be used to XYZ Summon Soul Of Silvermountain. Des Lacooda is a Zombie monster however, and cannot be protected by Catapult Zone, but can still trigger the effect of Exxod due to it's EARTH attribute. Attack The Moon is fantastic when you have at least 1 monster that can be flipped. Once per turn, when a Rock monster changes it's battle position, you destroy one of your opponents Spell/Traps. Flipping a monster face-up is a position change. There are also 2 Dust Tornadoes for a little more coverage. Lastly, Staunch Defender can be used to force your opponents to attack monsters they cannot defeat, such as any Sphinx monster or Exxod. EXTRA DECK There are 4 different XYZ monsters, 3 of which require 2 Level 4 monsters, and only 1 that requires 2 Level 3's. Number 55: Gogogo Goliath lets you add Level 4 or lower EARTH monsters from your GY to your hand, recycling any defeated monsters. Gallant Granite is an amazing searcher, as he allows you to either add any Rock monster from your deck to your hand, or Special Summon one in face-down defense position, providing a very simple way to get your hands on Exxod or Pharaonic Guardian Sphinx, as well as summon the latter without having to Tribute Summon. Number 52: Diamond Crab King's rather complex effect can be strategically used to either provide a solid defensive wall, or unleash a devastating attack. Lastly, Soul Of Silvermountain, the only Rank 3 monster in the Extra Deck renders 2 of your opponent's set Spell/Traps from being used as long as it exists on the field. This deck is a lot of fun to use and has won me quite a bit of duels, both in real life, and in the Link Evolution video game. Feel free to share any ideas/strategies that you think might work better and I'll look into them.

deck_excerpt: One Sided Macro in PK, LET'S GO!!!
deck_description: This format is very gy heavy ,so I thought: "In which deck could I splash the dark law engine?" and the 1st deck which comes to mind is PK.  Instead of ending on 1 apolousa, 1 requim and 2 fog blades, we are ending on 1 apolousa, 2 Fog Blades and a Dark law.  So instead of going into break sword you're going into isolde. Then you can search a follow up and send 4 to special the shadow mist and search the mask change 2.  Why am I playing the Isolde package over just 3 mask change 2? Well 1. the equips aren't bricks aslong as you don't draw them in multiples [all of them (except phoenix blade) are extenders] and 2. if your opponent drops a nibiru or a lancea you can still go into isolde and get your follow up + the dark law.

deck_excerpt: Now with Golden-Eyes Idol and a few secret tricks, Eyes Restrict has never been better!
deck_description:
New and improved! I've trimmed the fat, boosted the consistency, and added Dragoon for a reliable Turn 1 play.
  • Your two normal summons are Tour Guide and Ophrys Scorpio; use whichever is needed in the moment. Targets for Tour Guide are Sangan (searching Relinquished or M-E Illusionist) and Djinn (protecting your Relinquished).
  • If you don't feel like running Golden-Eyes Idol, just use Thousand-Eyes Idol + Advanced Ritual Art, plus whatever extra card suits your fancy.
  • Grisaille Prison is a cheeky little side deck option against Synchro and Xyz strategies—it will reliably shut down their entire gameplan. However, you'll want to wait until they've summoned at least one big Extra Deck monster before you activate it. Otherwise your Eyes Restricts will have no targets.
  • If you want to side in the Kaiju package, I recommend siding out the Predaplants, Djinn, Golden-Eyes, and Faceless Illusionist. None of those pieces is necessary to your core gameplan.

This deck uses the hunders to go into utopia package pretty easely, also i use wonder xyz, in the case i have thunder sea horse, so i can use to utopia combo during the opponent turn. I also use thunder king and denko, forsome lockdown plays and also vylon prism for summoning crimsom blader, which is very good against any monster who has a level, with level 5 or higher (aka dragoon). So the basic combo is the following: having pa/ma and another level 4 light thunder type monster:
  • Normal summon pa/ma;
  • Uses pa/ma effect to normal summon another level 4 light thunder type monster;
  • Overlay both monsters into utopia double;
  • Detach a material from double tosearch double or nothing and to summon utopia dragner;
  • Double detach from utopia dragner to summon hoping harbing, if youre going first, or utopia beyond, if youre going second
The ending board is dragner, who can turn the atk of one attacking monster 0, and hoping harbinger, who can negate the effect of a spell card once per turn, and thats not counting the extenders like double summon and recycling battle or handtraps. You can do combos a little bit biggers, but the basic board is this. If you draw thunder sea horse, a level 4 light thunder monster and wonder xyz, you can do this basic board during the opponent turn, because utopia double and utopiadragnereffects are quick effects.

deck_excerpt: In all honesty, the Japanese uncensored artwork is better, for 2 obvious reasons :}
deck_description: A Harpie Lady deck? How original. Hasn't this been done to death by now? Probably so. But that isn't going to stop me. Aside from Summoned Skull, the Harpies are my favorite Yu-Gi-Oh monsters, so naturally, this had to be done. Now I could add some variety to this and mix in another archetype like Mist Valley or Blackwind, but I'm not gonna. This is going to be Pure Harpie. Because reasons. Most people have probably seen this a million times, and I wouldn't be surprised if this exact same deck has already been created (I made this from scratch in LoTD Link Evolution), so because the effects are so complex, and most people know what to expect, I'll just cover some combos you can do using this setup. The basic theme of the deck is swarming the field with average-sized boobed bird-ladies that summon a baby dragon that can destroy whatever it wants because it can. The only thing this deck lacks is jiggle physics. BASIC SWARM/HARPIE'S PET BABY DRAGON: Normal Summon Harpie Channeler, use Elegant Egotist to Special Summon either Harpie Lady 1, or Harpie Lady Sisters, then use Harpie Channeler's effect to Special Summon Harpie's Pet Baby Dragon by discarding Harpie Harpist. When a Dragon monster is on the field, Harpie Channeler becomes Level 7. Harpie Oracle can be Special Summoned when there is a Level 5 or higher Harpie monster present. You now have at least 3 Harpie monsters on the field, activating all 3 of Harpie's Pet Baby Dragon's effects. During the End Phase, the effects of Harpie Harpist in the GY and Harpie Oracle on the field will activate. Harpist adds a Winged-Beast with 1500 or less ATK from the deck to the hand, and Oracle allows you to retrieve a card from the GY that has "Harpie Lady Sisters" in it's text, in this case, Elegant Egotist. STAY STOCKED: Any turn after activating Hysteric Sign, when it is destroyed, you can add 3 different Harpie cards from your deck to your hand. Once it's successfully activated, use one of these scenarios to quickly destroy it and fill your hand with the important things: 1). Link Summon Harpie Conductor, declare an attack on a monster you can't defeat, then activate her effect to destroy a Spell/Trap you control instead, destroy Hysteric Sign. 2). Play Harpie's Hunting Ground, summon a Harpie monster to trigger it's effect, destroy Hysteric Sign. Of course, you could just wait for a monster to be targeted for an attack and use Harpie Conductor to activate her effect, but doing it with method #1 is obviously quicker. 6000 LP OR LESS = 3 TURN WIN: If your opponent has 6000 or less Life Points, you can win the match within 3 turns assuming nothing happens to prevent the following setup. Use 3 Level 4 WIND monsters to XYZ Summon Harpie's Pet Phantasmal Dragon. It's effect not only allows you to attack your opponent directly, but it also protects all of your Harpie monsters from being targeted by effects or attacks, as long as it has material. At the End Phase of each turn, 1 material is detached. Mirror Force, Raigeki, and similar cards, or attack prevention such as Swords Of Revealing Light are the only way to stop this dragon's onslaught while it still has material. Other useful cards: Harpie's Pet Dragon: This sexy dragon has fantastic ATK/DEF which only climbs higher the more Harpie Ladies you have. With a full field of 5 Harpie Ladies, it's attack can reach 3500. If 3 of the monsters are Harpie Lady 1, it will reach maximum power at 4400. Alluring Mirror Split: When a Harpie Lady is destroyed by battle, Special Summon a replacement. Hysteric Party: Did your opponent just activate a Mirror Force? That's cute. Keep 1 card in your hand to use this Trap and get all your Harpie monsters right back after they are slain. Three Of A Kind: After using the BASIC SWARM strategy explained earlier, this card can be activated, which destroys 3 cards your opponent controls. Combined with Harpie's Pet Baby Dragon, you can rid the field of 4 of your opponent's cards during a single Main Phase. Harpie's Feather Storm: A Hand-Trap that protects you from monster effects for an entire turn. Cyber Slash Harpie Lady: The strongest un-boosted monster in the deck, which doesn't require any outside Tuner monsters due to her awesome transformation effect. This a versatile archetype with lots of other Harpie cards bearing similar effects. Capable of swarming and destruction, there are other honorable mentions such as Birdface, Harpie Dancer, and Harpie Lady Phoenix Formation, among others. This is just the setup I've found to be the most reliable. You could also incorporate other archetypes that synergize well with Winged Beasts and/or WIND monsters, but as I've said before, I prefer pure Harpie. This deck is so much fun. It's won me lots of duels and is one of my favorites to use. It might not be meta, but it sure packs one heck of a punch.

The next turn, you can activate Wandering King Wildwind from your GY to add Chain Resonator from your deck to your hand. Normal Summon Chain Resonator, use his effect to Special Summon any Resonator from your Deck. Synchro Summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Bane using Chain Resonator and Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss. Combo, ice bell = shenshen + revival setup via cloud castle  This combo is relatively simple and pretty rewarding overall because it only takes one card (two if you unluckily open rasenryu)  starting off similarly to the crystal wing combo but with a different ending, here’s my ShenShen Windwitch combo  Use ice bell to summon herself and Glass Bell  Have glass bell search freeze bell or snow bell, your pick  Use snow bell or freeze bell to summon herself from your hand  use Rasenryu’s effect from your deck or hand to send ice bell and freeze bell/snow bell to the graveyard to summon itself, fast fact, rasenryu can out dragoon if needed, if possible feel free to out something.  have glass bell tune rasenryu for shenshen, rasenryu searches possessed partnerships  set possessed partnerships.  if shenshen gets destroyed (correction when, this is a little frail) you can use possessed partnerships to summon glass bell (who has 1500 defense) and search blizzard bell, blizzard bell can be normal summoned with no tributes if all you own (if you own anything) are Windwitch’s, if you do that you can tune for cloudcastle and have it revive shenshen.  I’ll Wright down more combos when I have the time.

deck_excerpt: The goal is to U-link to shut down your opponent's special summoned monster effects
deck_description: To do the full combo you need either 1 formud skipper or any two crusadia (even two of the same name) except for arboria because you want to search for arboria off of magius to make Isolde using arboria and spatha.  This is the combo step by step:     1. Summon formud skipper  2. Activate formud skipper revealing spatha from the extra deck  3. Link formud skipper into magius  4. Use formud skipper's GY effect to search scrypton  5. Special summon scrypton to magius link point by banishing formud skipper from grave  6. Search arboria off of magius  7. Link magius and scrypton into spatha  8. Summon arboria to spatha's link point  9. Link spatha and arboria into Isolde  10. Search arboria off of Isolde using Isolde's first effect  11. Activate Isolde's second effect sending sword of deep-seated, cursed bamboo sword, horn of the unicorn, and Phoenix blade to special summon Armageddon knight  12. Sword of deep-seated activates (mandatory effect in grave) chain Armageddon as chain link 2 and cursed bamboo sword as chain link 3, search for broken bamboo sword and send zephyros off of armageddon knight  13. Equip broken bamboo sword to Armageddon knight then use zephyros effect to return it to hand to special summon itself from grave  14. Overlay Armageddon knight and zephyros into dugares  15. Activate dugares detaching two to special Armageddon knight from grave  16. Activate Armageddon knight sending summoner monk to grave  17. Link Isolde and Armageddon knight into akashic magician  18. Link akashic magician and dugares into selene (left extra monster zone)  19. (Selene places spell counters on herself on summon) remove 3 spell counters from selene to special summon summoner monk from grave  20. Activate summoner monk sending broken bamboo sword from hand to grave to special summon codebreaker zero day from deck  21. Link codebreaker zero day and summoner monk into codebreaker virus swordsman (under Selene's middle arrow)  22. Activate codebreaker virus swordsman summoning codebreaker zero day from grave (to Selene's link point)  23. Link codebreaker zero day and codebreaker virus swordsman into codebreaker virus berserker (same as virus swordsman summon it under Selene's middle arrow)  24. Activate codebreaker virus berserker summoning zero day and virus swordsman to Selene's open link points  25. Link codebreaker virus swordsman and selene into another selene (this time in the right extra monster zone)  26. Activate selene removing three spell counters to special summon summoner monk and activate Phoenix blade in grave banishing arboria and spatha to add Phoenix blade to hand  27. Activate summoner monk sending Phoenix blade to grave to summon rescue ferret from deck  28. Activate rescue ferret shuffling it back into the deck to summon witch of the black forest and plaguespreader zombie  29. Link codebreaker virus berserker and witch of the black forest into knightmare gryphon (to Selene's left most link marker)  30. Activate witch of the black forest searching for exodius  31. Link plaguespreader zombie and summoner monk into knightmare Cerberus (under Selene's middle arrow)  32. Activate plaguespreader zombie in grave placing the arboria in hand on top of the deck to special summon plaguespreader zombie  33. Link plaguespreader zombie and codebreaker zero day into crystron halqifibrax (under Selene's right arrow)  34. Activate halqifibrax effect summoning (another) plaguespreader zombie from deck  35. Activate Phoenix blade in grave banishing Armageddon knight and Isolde to add Phoenix blade to hand  36. Summon exodius from hand by shuffling all monsters in grave into the deck (and place any extra deck monsters back in the extra deck) (it's a summoning condition not an activated effect)  37. Link plaguespreader and exodius into knightmare Phoenix (to knightmare gryphon's left arrow)  38. Activate plaguespreader in grave placing the Phoenix blade on top of your deck to special itself from grave  39. Link halqifibrax and plaguespreader into knightmare unicorn (in the left extra monster zone)  The end result is 5 co-linked monsters in a U-link that can't be destroyed by battle or card effect (and unicorn draws you 4 cards each one of your draw steps because of the 4 co-linked knightmares)  (There is a way to work tri-gate wizard into it but you need a few extra extenders to do it)

deck_excerpt: Very fast and fun Utopia/Raidraptor/Time Thief OTK/FTK deck.
deck_description: This deck features several brutal OTK/FTK strategies, as well as some plain evil boss monsters. The boss monsters in this deck are as follows: Number 39: Utopia Beyond ARC Rebellion XYZ Dragon Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus - Sky Thunder Number 99: Utopic Dragon Borrelsword Dragon Accesscode Talker MAIN STRATEGY First, let's hope you have drawn a Time Thief Regulator, and that your opponent is going first. Let's also hope that your opponent ends their turn with a monster left in attack position that can be effected by your card effects. First, normal summon your Time Thief Regulator, summoning Time Thief Winder and Time Thief Bezel Ship from your deck. Summoning your Time Thief Winder will trigger its effect. Add Time Thief Adjuster to your hand using this effect. XYZ summon Number 39: Utopia Double, and then activate it by detaching Bezel Ship to add Double or Nothing! to your hand. Do not set Double or Nothing!. Special summon Number 39: Utopia Beyond, as the final part of Number 39: Utopia Double's effect, using Utopia Double as the XYZ material. This special summon will trigger Utopia Beyond's effect, changing all of your opponent's current face-up monsters' attack to 0. Utopia Beyond will also have 6000 attack permanently, and will not be able to attack directly due to Utopia Double's effect. Special summon Bezel Ship by its own effect, detaching a material from your XYZ monster. Special summoning Bezel ship will trigger Time Thief Adjuster's effect, special summoning it as well. XYZ summon Number 39: Utopia in attack position. Enter your battle phase. Declare an attack on any monster (You won't be able to attack directly) with Number 39: Utopia Beyond, but negate the attack with Utopia. Negating the attack will allow you to activate Double or Nothing!. Activate it. This will allow your Utopia Beyond to attack again, doubling it's attack during the damage step. If all goes well, your opponent will have lost all of their life points, taking 12000 damage at that time. You do not have to play exactly this strategy. It is just as easy to use Raidraptors to achieve this same end goal. There are many other strategies in this deck that can OTK/FTK as well. Be sure to experiment with this deck to find out which one you enjoy the most. The side deck is outfitted with cards to be able to handle meta deck such as Virtual Worlds, and even more sinister decks, such as Drytrons or Cubics.

deck_excerpt: Pure Dogmatika with no heretical usage of Invoked or Shaddolls
deck_description: Unless you've been living under a rock for a while, you've seen a good portion of these cards. The Dogmatikas. The bane of any extra deck-focused deck, which, when combined with Shaddolls and Invoked, forms a disgustingly powerful control deck. That's not what we're doing today. Today is all about the deck in its purest form.  The Dogmatikas are all about their crusade against the extra deck, so we'll barely ever use ours. I say barely because Dogmatikas cannot go first on their own. The best you can do is normal summon Ecclesia or Adin and set some traps to live until your next turn. Because of this, we're running Instant Fusion to summon out Millennium-Eyes Restrict which can be linked off into Linkuriboh to fulfil the conditions for every single summon except for Nexus and White Knight. However, Instant Fusion is currently sitting at 1, so you're rarely going to draw it in your opening hand. To fix this glaring issue, you can substitute Retort Fusion and use Kamionwizard to summon Magistus Maiden Artemis instead of the Linkuriboh play. You can also use Darkfire Dragon and summon out Striker Dragon to pretend you're doing a dragon link combo. Just be aware that the TCG doesn't exactly have this card yet, so if you get your hands on a playset of Retort Fusion and use it at an official tournament, you're gonna be disqualified.  So now, we come to the extra deck. As with all Dogmatika builds, you need to be careful about which cards you're dumping from your extra deck throughout your turn. N'tss is a non-OPT pop anything on the field so only send this when you have stuff to pop. Fossil Warrior Skull Knight is your extra copies of N'tss, but it comes with an upside. If you've already popped all the troublesome monsters on your opponent's field, he can just sit in grave until you're ready to use him. The goodest of bois. Titaniklad is pretty self-explanatory. He gives you a free summon from deck in the end phase (or a free search if you'd rather have that), but this effect is a hard OPT so you can't just dump 3 Titaniklad and build a board like that. Wind Pemasus @Ignister strikes fear into your opponent's heart as they constantly fear its effect to shuffl one of their monsters into the deck after they destroy one of yours. And finally, Herald of the Arc Light. Unlike every single synchro deck in recent memory, we only care about its ritual spell/monster search effect. This gets you White Knight who can dump Titaniklad using Dogmatikalamity to summon itself from hand.  Now it's time for the main deck. Most of these cards should be familiar. Ecclesia searches your archetype, Maximus sends 2 cards from both extra decks to grave, Fleurdelis boosts attack when your cards declare attacks and negates a monster's effects if you have another Dogmatika on field, Nadir Servant is the single-most busted search card in the game, and Punishment sends a card from your extra deck to the GY to destroy and opponent's monster as long as the attack is greater than that opponent's monster. As for the cards that you might not know, Adin is a free summon from hand that can float into any Dogmatika from deck (except Nexus and White Knight of course). White Knight lets you send a card from both extra decks to the GY when your opponent activates an effect. Ashiyan summons itself when an extra deck summon is sent to the GY and even adds a Dogmatika from grave back to hand as consolation. Nexus is your win condition. Lightning Storm on attack declaration and burns if it killed any extra deck monsters by the effect. Not to mention its amazing summon condition that lets you empty your opponents GY of extra deck monsters to summon itself.  As for spell cards, Called By is for handtrap insurance, Dwimmered Path adds any Dogmatika from GY to hand, Dogmatika Nation provides some protection to your Dogmatikas, and Dogmatikacism gives you some way to lower an opponent's monster's attack and gives you a free extra deck dump when that monster is destroyed. Handtraps are handtraps, and you can sub out the ones I used for whichever fit the scene you're in. Same with the handtraps in the side deck. As for the 3 extra deck monsters in the side deck, you can sub these in if you refuse to give in to the temptation of the extra deck. Omega recurs resources, Link God is the biggest technically-summonable send for Punishment, and the third Fossil Warrior is like the other 2 Fossil Warriors, but he's actually happy to be here.  There's quite a few other options you can run in the deck if you want to. Almiraj helps with that whole "you have almost zero way to set up a board first turn" by using Adin as its link material. Mega Zaborg can dump 8 cards from both extra decks on summon, but like all Monarchs, he tends to brick your hands more often than not. Theo is bad. But he's also a Dogmatika if you really want the whole church present. Just don't play more than one. Dogmatika Encounter and Genesis are also quite bad. But if you run into an issue known as "my opponent refuses to summon from the extra deck", Encounter can help get your monsters on field. Genesis is still really situational though, so only run that if you know you'll be able to fulfil its activation requirements consistently. Kaijus and their like do what they've always done and eat your opponent's boss monsters before they become an issue. Lightning Storm is Lightning Storm and since you're almost always going second, it can help deal with backrow decks. Forbidden Droplets is even more insurance against your opponent's bunguses. If you lack any integrity, Rivalry of Warlords, Gozen Match, and Secret Village of the Spellcasters can also be played. But in that case, why not just play the Invoked Shaddoll heresy deck instead.

So utopia's are actually a viable option of competitive play right now thanks to the introduction of a lot of cards.  Utopic astral hope makes xyz change tactics searchable giving this deck a powerful draw engine , which can easily lead into a +3-+8 in card advantage.  Utopic Future dragon makes the future archetype viable giving a monster eff negate and potential monster steal.  Utopic sage + Gaga guardian gives this deck two useful non number cards to summon future with.  This deck can easily lead into a board with 2-3 monster negates and multiple 4000+ attack point monsters on a first turn hand.  Running ZW's make this deck prone to bricking so keeping this deck staple light. Dark ruler no more/ Called by the grave are important to stop hand and field negations, and solemn judgement and numbers protect give this deck some much needed omni negates. Harpie's feather duster is for backrow.

deck_excerpt: Make Lambda and Redoer for shennanigans
deck_description: The strategy is stalling to turn 2 with a stunning strategy following the cards Redoer and Lambda (Redoer triggers Lambda and a detached Emerald Bird/Yellow Marten) + I:P (I:P uses the PSY-frames summoned during your opponent's turn as material). If you stall successfully, during turn 2 you can go into Leo Dancer using Chick as material which turns off all the opponent's effects when banished (Wolf banishes the materials for its fusion effect) securing you the win. You make Leo by ditching Wolf+Panther with Chick, then making Tiger King searching Black Sheep. Black Sheep re-adds Wolf and then you can fusion summon. Notable cards are Whelp + Destruction Sword. Whelp sends Destruction Sword to the GY, which you can use to pitch either Perfume or Serenade Dance. Destruction Sword then acts as discard fodder for either of the 2. Keep in mind that Perfume can trigger the Dangers but the same cannot be said about Serenade Dance.

deck_excerpt: The ultimate Dark Magician Deck without broken Red-Eyes Dragoon, win your matches with pride.
deck_description: The ultimate Dark Magician Deck without broken Red-Eyes Dragoon, win your matches with pride.

This deck involves using Dark Magician Girl and the other Magician Girl cards to summon either themselves or summon bigger monsters in the Extra Deck.  Some combos include using Magician's Restage to summon Magicians' Souls and using Magicians' Souls to send it to the graveyard to draw cards. Magician's Restage also works on Berry Magician Girl. Magician's Restage is also useful in summoning Predaplant Verte Anaconda.  Using Eye of Timaeus, you can summon either Dragoon or Dark Magician Girl the Dragon Knight. One of my favorite things to do with this deck is using the effect of Kiwi Magician Girl to increase Dark Magician Girl the Dragon Knight's attack to higher levels to beat over foes, since nothing's more humiliating than losing to Dark Magician Girls in general.  Of course there's always the tried and tested Predaplant Verte Anaconda into Dragoon combo that's in nearly every deck nowadays. There's also the summoning of Divine Arsenal AA Zeus from two level ones including Magicians' Souls or Berry Magician Girl.  This deck also includes Ash Blossom and Solemn Judgement, although these can switched out for any other hand traps or field traps of your liking, these are the ones I went with.

deck_excerpt: The publisher announced the new titles during the Yu-Gi-Oh! Digital Next event, with one title planned to release this Fall.
deck_description: Konami has revealed three, new digital titles for Yu-Gi-Oh!, Master Duel, Rush Duel and Cross Duel, advancing the digital TCG to new heights. The publisher announced the new titles during the Yu-Gi-Oh! Digital Next event, with one title planned to release this Fall. Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links will also be receiving an exciting new addition called Arc-V World, and we’ve explored each new title below. https://communities.sgna.org/blogs/rapidos-furiosos/2021/07/24/rapidos-y-furiosos-9-2021-ver-pelicula-completa-on https://connect.dona.org/blogs/stream-vod/2021/07/24/rapidos-y-furiosos-9-pelicula-completa-donde-ver YU-GI-OH! MASTER DUEL Master Duel will be released worldwide on PlayStation 5, PlayStation 4, Xbox Series X/S, Xbox One, Nintendo Switch, Steam, iOS and Android, with a release date yet to be announced. Master Duel is tailored to veteran duelists whilst also equipped to welcome new players to the world of the Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game in digital form. Konami is confident that Master Duel is the “most complete” Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG digital title yet, and for the first time ever, the game will feature 4K graphics on supported devices. YU-GI-OH! RUSH DUEL Rush Duel is Konami’s working title for the worldwide release of the digital Japanese card game of the same name, releasing on the Nintendo Switch this Fall. Based on the anime Yu-Gi-Oh! Sevens, Rush Duel introduces a new ruleset for speedy duels, where you can continuously draw and summon. Once the new rules are mastered, duelists can begin to collect Rush Duel cards to build their own Decks. Popular Yu-Gi-Oh! Sevens characters can also be challenged in Rush Duel, as well as other duelists from around the world. YU-GI-OH! CROSS DUEL Cross Duel is an exciting new title for iOS and Android, with more details on the mobile project expected to be announced soon. Cross Duel will introduce multiplayer action with fast-paced, four-player Duels. YU-GI-OH! ARC-V WORLD FOR DUEL LINKS The hit title Duel Links, available on iOS, Android and PC Steam, will also be welcoming Yu-Gi-Oh! Arc-V World, which will be arriving in-game soon. Based on the anime Yu-Gi-Oh! Arc-V, this addition will likely follow the show’s four-dimensional setting, where there is an alternate Extra Deck Special Summon method for each. Konami highlighted Duel Link’s success with over 140 million downloads worldwide, in addition to more than 65 billion cards collected and 6 billion Duels performed.

deck_excerpt: Stop your opponent from doing anything with three simple cards
deck_description: This deck focusses mostly on a three card lockdown: Starduston, Mystic Mine and Anti-Spell Fragrance. With all of them on the field, your opponent can not: (Attack | Special Summon | Set monsters | activate Spells/Traps ).  In other words, they can do nothing. This far, I could only make out two cards that could threaten this combo: Volcanic Queen and Galaxy Cyclone. Both of those are run very rarely if ever. Normal Kaijus don't work because your opponent cannot special summon. Sphere mode and Lava Golem don't work because you never want to have more than one monster on the field after resolving your combo. And other Spell/Trap removal options don't work because they can't be activated from the field.     Your core strategy is this:  Summon House Duston/Stygian Security  Run into the enemies monster and special summon as many Dustons as possible to either side of the field. (make sure to give your opponent at least two dustons, except white or house duston).  Activate Mystic Mine and set Anti-Spell fragrance.  Activate Ant-Spell Fragrance during your opponents draw phase and Viola, you won the duel.  Now don't attack but wait for your opponent to deck out, as to not accidentaly blow up Starduston or Mystic Mine.
Pray for Utopia GOD!!

deck_description: I've been collecting and modding this deck since the 5Ds era when I got Malefic Blue-Eyes from K-Mart. The side deck to this Blue-Eyes project is still getting edited, so I'll add that when I'm done. Hopefully though, since I'm not as lucky as some other players, this deck can be good enough without a side deck.

Some tips:
  • If you don't start the duel with "ZS - Ascend Sage", start your combo with the XYZ Summon of "ZS - Utopic Sage", because the second throws the first one onto the field, which in turn seeks its "Rank-Up" spells .
  • You can summon "Leo Utopia Ray" using the "Number 99: Utopia Bringer" effect. Therefore, the "Rank-Up" magic that you will look for the most is the "Hope Force", helping to summon the "Utopia Bringer". Before activating the "Rank-Up" magic, invoke the classic "Utopia Ray" on top of Utopia, to get more xyz-materials, and you can use the "Utopia Bringer" effect once more.

deck_excerpt: Exodia stall deck with Mystic Mine, uses Draw of Fate as a combo piece
deck_description: Win with Exodia  Step 1- Set up Mystic Mine. Can be done through draw power, metaverse, or terraforming. Swift Scarecrow and One Day of Peace can stall  Protect Mystic Mine with Dark Bride + Solemn Judgement  Step 2- Get 2 Exodia pieces in hand  This makes what I've found to be the best combo usually an instant win  Use draw power cards to get 2 pieces quickly  Step 3- Activate Draw of Fate combo  **Make sure your life points are lower than your opponents. This can be done with Cosmic Cyclone, Solemn Judgement, or Upstart Goblin  If you have the 2 pieces in hand, search the remaining 3 pieces with Draw of Fate  You will draw 1 for the effect of Draw of Fate  Then activate Cardcar D, Reckless Greed, or Pot of Extravagance to draw the final 2 pieces

deck_excerpt: Nothing like making plays with your opponent monsters...
deck_description:
As a follow-up of the Triple SD Challenge for the Freezing Chains Structure Deck, I here post the Triple SD Challenge for the Spirit Charmers Structure Deck. But first, since I went through some trouble building the deck due to motives explained below, I changed the rules for the challenge and take a similar approach to some special decklists posted on OCG. That rule being that I know must use, at least, 30 cards on my Main Deck that belong on the original card list of the Structure Deck, where having multiple copies of a card will count. But the 40-card Main deck rule stays. Now, as for the achetype itself, the Spirit Charmer Structure Deck actually covers 3 sub-archtypes linked together by their playstyle; those being Charmers, Familiar-Possessed and Awakening of the Possessed. Charmers are a series of Level 3 Spellcaster-Type Flip monsters with 500 Atk/1500 Def with share the effect that if the card is flipped, you can target one monster your opponent controls that shares its attribute and take control of it while the Flip monster remains on the field. This Flip monster also cover all attributes on the game, except DIVINE: Eria for WATER, Hiita for FIRE, Aussa for EARTH, Wynn (not Winda, and no, not that one) for WIND, Lyna for LIGHT and Dharc for DARK. Familiar-Possessed are a series of Level 4 Spellcaster-Type monsters with 1850 Atk/1500 Def that represent an "upgraded" form of all 6 Charmers. All of them can be Special Summoned from the hand or Deck by sending their respective Charmer monster and a face-up monster on your side of the field with the same attribute as that Charmer monster. Also, if summoned by this method, all of them can deal piercing damage. However, Lyna and Dharc have an additional effect: Lyna can add 1 Spellcaster-Type monster with 1500 Def from your Deck to your hand, while Dharc can add 1 Level 3 or 4 LIGHT Spellcaster monster. Finally, Awakening of the Possessed consists of Level 5 monsters with 2000 Atk/200 Def that can also be Special Summoned from the hand or deck by sending a face-up Spellcaster-type monster and a face-up Level 4 or lower monster with the same attribute as the Level 5 monster, where in this case there isn't a LIGHT or DARK monster. All of them have an effect when summoned by their summoning condition and a floating effect:
  • Rasenryu (WIND): Return a card your opponent controls to the hand, without targeting. If is sent from the field to the GY: Add either a "Possessed" Spell/Trap or "Spiritual Wind Art - Miyabi" from the Deck to your hand.
  • Nefariouser Archfiend (EARTH): Special Summon a Level 4 or lower monster from the GY with its effects negated. If is sent from the field to the GY: Add either a "Possessed" Spell/Trap or "Spiritual Earth Art - Kurogane" from the Deck to your hand.
  • Gagigobyte (WATER): Send a random card from your opponent's hand to the GY, then, both players draws 1 card. If is sent from the field to the GY: Add either a "Possessed" Spell/Trap or "Spiritual Water Art - Aoi" from the Deck to your hand.
  • Greater Inari Fire (FIRE): Burn your opponent equal to the original ATK of 1 monster they control (you can chose the target, but by how the effect is written, it actually doesn't target). If is sent from the field to the GY: Add either a "Possessed" Spell/Trap or "Spiritual Fire Art - Kurenai" from the Deck to your hand.
For their new support of the Structure Deck (at last, after overexplaining the archtype): Spirit Charmers is a interesting card. As a Quick-Play Spell, you can discard a card to take 2 cards from your deck that are either "Charmer" monsters, "Familiar-Possessed" monsters or "Possessed" Spells/Traps; then you will add 1 of them to your hand and the other is Set on the field. It can summon the Flip monsters face-down from the Deck, searches backrow, which is really good, and adds consistency to the Deck. It think is obvious you run 3. Awakening of the Possessed (AotP for short), not the series of monsters, is a Continuous Spell with 3 effects, where only the last one is a hard OPT:
  • ALL MONSTERS YOU CONTROL gain 300 ATK for each different Attribute you control. And yes, it can stack with multiple copies of itself, like TGX300 or Solidarity.
  • "Charmer" and "Familiar-Possessed" monsters you control cannot be destroyed by card effects.
  • As the hard OPT, if you Normal or Special Summon a Spellcaster monster with 1850 ORIGINAL ATK, draw 1 card (is mandatory, for some reason).
Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin is their Field Spell that negates the first monster effect used by your opponent as long as you control a Spellcaster monster with 1500 Def. It also has an additional effect to search monsters with 1500 Atk/200 Def, but is mainly played due to the negate. Moving to the traps, Possessed Partnerships is a Normal Trap that Special Summons a Spellcaster monster with 1500 Def from your hand or GY, and then destroys a face-up card on the field if you control 2 or more different Attributes. It can also banish itself from the GY to place a "Possessed" Continuous Spell/Trap from the GY on the field, face-up. The last card is Unpossessed, a Continuous Trap with 3 effects, the last one being a hard OPT, like AotP:
  • "Charmer" monster cannot be destroyed by battle, helping to their playstyle and to maintain control of the stolen monster.
  • "Familiar-Possessed" monsters gains 800 ATK when attacking an opponents monster. (They don't get ATK with direct attacks or while being attacked).
  • The hard OPT, and oh boy this is a mouthful, is that if a monster(s) is destroyed by any means while this card is already face-up on the field: You can Special Summon from your Deck a Spellcaster monster with 1500 Def in Attack Position or face-down Defense Position, but its Attribute must be different from the destroyed monster(s).
For the outside support, and the reason I made the new rule, are the following:
  • Dharc & Lyna: For some reason, the Structure Deck does not come with Dharc & Lyna, despite they covering some of the most popular Attributes ever played, and also being the Attributes with the most amount of monsters. For that reason, and also for the possible search their "Familiar-Possessed" do, I added them to the mix.
 
  • Eda the Sun Magician: If Normal or Flip Summoned, it can Special Summon any Spellcaster monster with 1500 Def from the Deck in face-down Defense Position. During the opponent's turn, as a Quick-Play, can flip a face-down Spellcaster monster to face-up Attack Position. I add it for placing an specific "Charmer" monster on the field and then use it for disruption for the opponent's turn, possibly stealing a playmaker, that is if they aren't destroyed beforehand.
 
  • There are no Extra Deck monsters on the Structure Deck, not even the Link-2 Charmers. You can go wild in this section, but for my recommendation, I suggest both Lyna and Aussa for Attribute coverage and to steal monsters for link climbing, Selene for revival of the Main Deck Spellcasters and also link climbing, any Link-4 or higher monster that is generic (I went with Borrelsword Dragon and Underworld Goddess), Day-Breaker for a bit of extra removal, and finally, any R4NK Xyz Monster (I decided for Tornado Dragon for backrow removal and The Lightning package).
Anyway, I hope you enjoy the decklist and for the next time, it will be the Obelisk and Slifer Structure Decks. Until next time!

deck_excerpt: Red dragon archfiend deck using edge imps.
deck_description: The deck can make some very strong plays. Mainly going for red super nova dragon which is really hard to deal with for some decks. The deck can also easily OTK with quite a lot of special summons and high ATK dragons. The main problem is that the deck runs out of resources very fast and has only little recovery due to red rising dragon's and ede imp saber's GY effects. Super polymerization just destroys the deck most of the time. Other hand traps are also very problematic to deal with. The main play of the deck is to summon crimson resonator and edge imp tomahawk which mills edge imp sabers. Then synchro for red rising dragon, summon back crimson resonator, summon creation and synkron resonator with crimson, go for red super nova dragon, add creation resonator back with synkron resonator and summon it, then summon edge imp sabers, synchro for another red rising dragon and go for red dragon archfiend abyss to get a negate.  https://youtu.be/xNoID6bXtN8

deck_excerpt: Tribute summon with options going first and going second
deck_description: Would like to have some help making the deck better.     Anyway, the best going first board is Mithra - tribute for Thestalos - Mithra effect for an extra tribute summon and tribute Thestalos for Erebus (shuffle a card from hand), send Pantheism and anything (preferably The Prime) then banish Pan for two domains and a Tenacity if you have another monarch in hand or an Erupt if you don't. This rips two cards and establishes what I call 'The Monarch Lock'. Domain with a Monarch locks out of extra deck, and if you have a majesty's then you also get a monster effect lock. You can also just use Erupt as your monster effect lock. Most of the time, the extra deck lock can really shut down some decks and if it doesn't, game two you can side for something like sphere mode or another Caius the mega monarch.  This may sound confusing but trust me this deck is pretty simple to understand.     Again, any suggestions are appreciated.

deck_excerpt: My updated Adamancipator Dragoon deck with some fossil cards to add some flexibility or as an extender
deck_description: The goal of the deck is to turbo Borreload Savage Dragon and Dragun of Red-Eyes, Optimal opening would be a lvl 4 rock, Adamancipator Researcher and Adamancipator Seeker. Normal the lvl 4 rock -> Activate Researcher -> activate Analyzer. Use the effect of Researcher and Analyzer you are looking to hit Adamancipator Crystal Dragite to draw a card or Koa'Ki Mieru Guardian to protect the board or plays. Synchro into Adamancipator Risen Raptite to special a rock from top 5. Link 2 for Crystron Halqifibrax to special Researcher or Seeker. Link 2 for Predaplant Verte Anaconda using Halqifibrax. Synchro into Borreload then equip Halqifibrax. Activate Verte Anaconda to send Red-Eyes Fusion, Red-Eyes Black Dragon and Dark Magician from the deck to the graveyard. The Fossil Engine is used to create beaters in the grind game or to make a material to extend plays. A 2 card combo would be Miracle Rupture and Adamancipator Signs. Use Rupture to send Dragite from deck to grave and then use signs to Special Dragite from the GY. Use the effects to add Researcher or Seeker to the top of the deck then draw with Dragite to start your combo. Problems are bricking with Dragun materials and being unable to extend from a handtrap or whiff.

This deck was nerfed recently and should be now used alongside a dragunity engine. Since Elpy now is banned, you can replace it with Hieratic King Dragon of Atum instead. Basic combo: 1 Dragunity Remus + 1 Random Card: Discard Remus to add Ravine to your hand, then activate Ravine to discard 1 random card and add Legatus to your hand. Special Summon Legatus from hand first and then Remus from your GY due to their own effects. Then, Synchro into Gae Dearg and activate Gae Dearg to add and discard Zephyros. Zephyros 's effect in GY allows you to bounce Dragon Ravine to Special Summon him with a cost of 400 LP. Now Link into Romulus then add Dragunity Glow due to its effect. Now activate Glow to add Mystletainn to your hand and special summon it by tributing Romulus. Now activate Mystletainn's effect to equip Gae Dearg from your GY to Mystletainn. Next, activate Glow in your GY to banish itself in order to SSummon Gae Dearg from S/T zone. Then active Gae Dearg again to add and discard your Chamber Maid. Overlay 2 level 6 dragunity on your field into Atum. Now use Atum to detach Gae Dearg and SSummon Darkness Metal from your Deck (DMetal should be in Defense Position bc its ATK/DEF will be 0). Now activate DMetal to SSummon Gae Dearg from GY once again then activate Gae Dearg again to add and discard Baby Roc and immediately SSummon Baby Roc. That is the basic 1 card-combo. It will end up you having 4 monsters on the field and then you can link your monster into anything your like (L2 Spheres to bounce your opponent's monster, L4 Borrelsword of Apollousa for main beater or negations, or L2 Whelp, send Dragon Buster to the GY and somehow equip it to one of your beater by DMZ Dragon to lock your opponent from SSummon from his/her Extra). After that, you can still make better board using remain cards in your hand. Here's some ways:
  • Now if you still have Ravine in your hand and 1 card, you can either use Ravine to send Absorouter in order to add Tracer to your hand, NSummon it, destroy Ravine by its effect and go for Crystal Wing, Chaos Ruler or Borreload Savage (equip it with Romulus and get 2 negates), OR send White or Black Dragon to GY to get the remain, SSummon it and link for Pisty and revive some Dragon
  • If you have World Legacy Guardragon, it's great bc you can use it with Ravine to perform many nice play, like making 1-level 8 synchro (Chaos Ruler or Savage Dragon, but I prefer Chaos Ruler 'cause it can get Synchron by chance with its effect and it can be easily revived) then somehow, mostly by SSummon your Rokket Synchron back with WLG which was luckily send to GY by Chaos Ruler effect or Ravine (if you have multiple copies of it in your hand), to synchro into Hot Red Dragon
Advantages: -Short combos and not complicated -Multiple negations and attacks with huge ATK in case you make the best board -Hard to break after being made successful -Multiple ways to start combo (Dragunity Start Combo, Rokket Start Combo, White/Black Dragon Start Combo) -Multiple ways to beat your opponent (Borreload S. Dragon, Crystal Wing, Hot Red Dragon and mostly Borrelsword D.) Drawbacks: -Totally stopped and destroyed by hand traps -Can easily trigger your OP 's nibiru -Due to the banlist, it's now weaker than many decks (Drytron, Tri-Brigade, Shaddoll) -Can be destructed by multiple destroying unstoppable cards (Accesscode Talker)

It's a bunch of recycling. I made a deck like this about three years as just a fun casual deck to get me back a little into Yu-Gi-Oh and I didn't realize how much some of these cards are now. So definitely not a budget deck but I wanted to add some stuff to it and all of the cards I added are inexpensive so I think you can salvage something for a budget if you wanna try it out. I have yet to try this one out yet so once I can add the cheap cards I'll test it and depending on the results I might edit this or leave it. This was just a way to visualize how I would mix up the deck and what cards I'm going to add.

Use multiple cards in your hand to send to GY or add to hand your 4 dimensional magicians by Harmonizing Magician or Timestar Magician. I use 3 copies of Timestar BC I think it's necessary to have your magicians in your hand and your Chronograph Sorcerer out. If you aren't enough lucky to have your Z-ARC out in your first turn, use Number F0 to survive through turns and Tornado Dragon + Double Iris Magician in order to get more magicians or destroy OP 's monsters or backrows with 02 Pendulumgraph cards.
ORCUST-PK top 8 locals (July 2021)

deck_name: Destiny HERO - Post Burst of Destiny
deck_description: In this deck you will want to have on the field Destroy Phoenix Enforcer + Dominance. And the following D-HERO monsters in the GY: Malicious, Denial, Dreadmaster, Disk Commander and Drawhand. With that said, on your opponent's standby phase you'll want to activate Phoenix's effect do destroy anything along with your Dominance, so you can have Denial, Dreadmaster and Disk Commander being summoned.  When that happens, all your D-HERO monsters will be indestructible by card effects and battle. Also, you'll take no damage in battle that involves D-HERO monsters.  With that said, activate Disk Commander in chain 1 + Denial in Chain 2. With Denial's effect, put Plasma on top of your deck.  With Disk commander's effect, you draw 2 cards.  You can also let Drawhand join the field party and allow it to make each duelist draw a card if you have a Droll & Lock Bird in hands. This is the cherry on top.  There you have it. Indestructible monsters on the field ready to be tributed for plasma on your next turn.

deck_excerpt: Summon Number F0: Utopic Draco Future alongside Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon and D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga!  Youtube: TCG Raidraptors
deck_description:
The Default Combo is as follows:
  1. Normal Summon Raidraptor - Vanishing Lanius
  2. Special Summon Raidraptor - Mimicry Lanius by Raidraptor - Vanishing Lanius effect
  3. XYZ Summon Raidraptor - Force Strix
  4. Detach Raidraptor - Mimicry Lanius to activate Raidraptor - Force Strix and search for Raidraptor - Singing Lanius
  5. Special Summon Raidraptor - Singing Lanius
  6. Activate Raidraptor - Mimicry Lanius effect to search for Raidraptor - Nest
  7. Activate Raidraptor - Nest to search for Raidraptor - Pain Lanius
  8. Special Summon Raidraptor - Pain Lanius by targeting Raidraptor - Singing Lanius
  9. Link Summon Raidraptor - Wise Strix using Raidraptor - Force Strix and Raidraptor - Pain Lanius
  10. Special Summon Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite with Raidraptor - Wise Strix effect
  11. XYZ Summon Raider's Knight using Raidraptor - Singing Lanius and Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite
  12. Detach Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite to activate Raider's Knight and XYZ Summon Raidraptor - Stranger Falcon chaining Raidraptor - Wise Strix to set Rank-Up-Magic Skip Force
  13. Activate Rank-Up-Magic Skip Force to XYZ Summon Raidraptor - Arsenal Falcon
  14. Detach Raider's Knight to activate Raidraptor - Arsenal Falcon and Special Summon Raidraptor - Vanishing Lanius
  15. Link Summon The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche using Raidraptor - Arsenal Falcon and Raidraptor - Wise Strix chaining Raidraptor - Arsenal Falcon to XYZ Summon Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon
  16. Activate The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche to send Raider's Wing from the deck to the grave and set The Phantom Knight's Rank-Up-Magic Launch
  17. Activate Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite in the grave to Special Summon to the field and return Raidraptor - Nest to the hand
  18. Activate Raidraptor - Vanishing Lanius effect to Special Summon Raidraptor - Vanishing Lanius from hand
  19. XYZ Summon Gagagaga Magician using Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite and Raidraptor - Vanishing Lanius
  20. Activate Gagagaga Magician to Special Summon Raidraptor - Force Strix from the grave
  21. Activate Raider's Wing in the grave to detach Blackwing - Zephyros from Gagagaga Magician and Special Summon to the field
  22. XYZ Summon Number F0: Utopic Future using Gagagaga Magician and Raidraptor - Force Strix
  23. XYZ Summon Number F0: Utopic Draco Future using Number F0: Utopic Future
  24. XYZ Summon Number 39: Utopia Double using Raidraptor - Vanishing Lanius and Raider's Wing
  25. Activate Number 39: Utopia Double to search for Double or Nothing! and XYZ Summon Number 93: Utopia Kaiser
  26. Activate Number 93: Utopia Kaiser to Special Summon Number 11: Big Eye
  27. On your opponent's turn, activate The Phantom Knight's Rank-Up-Magic Launch targeting Number 11: Big Eye to XYZ Summon D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga
Note: There are many variations of the combo using Raidraptor - Tribute Lanius or the pendulum engine.  The only dead card in hand is Double or Nothing!. The Rank-Up-Magic cards in hand will only shorten the combo. The combo can be viewed on this Youtube Channel: https://youtu.be/3tQgllbS7fc

He has a large appreciation for Shogi, and even uses Duel Monsters cards whose both design and effects are based on the board game. Hishakaku uses a "Line Monster" Deck, whose effects are based on a card's position on the field. deck_name: Infernoid deck 2021 -  MY brother YCS SA attempt
deck_excerpt: Skinner!!! The house is on fire!!!
deck_description: This is the first guid oa a deck written by my brother, being  his YCS remote duel SA choice. I hope you enjoy his guide as much as I do.   Eternal fire   The almighty fire fiends of the great sacred tree are useful once again in this modern format . You can ask why or maybe how, and I will have answers for both questions .  First of all, basically every infernoid is a D. D. Crow, it means that there is no card in GY safe from being banished when these fiends hit the field . On top of that, the archetype’s big monsters can fully clean the field, monsters and back row. Now, let’s go to how the deck functions and why I built it like that:   MONSTER:   I don’t want to set world on fire crew:   Antra, Harmadik and Patrulea are here to serve as food to the bigger infernoids or for a quick answer to any threat in the field using Decatron . Antra bounces anything, Harmadik destroys one monster and Patrulea destroys one spell/trap, and also, they have the common quick effect of banishing any card in gy, only with a cost to tribute one monster in field (including themselves).   Decatron is here for a lot of reasons (pun with reasoning). Reason 1: Reasoning and Monster Gate, with these two cards you can mill almost fully deck  given space to play with almost all the other infernoids, and in the end finish with its summoning and mill the last infernoid that you need. Reason 2, is an excellent fist bait for any interactions that your opponent might have. Reason 3, with the trap Void Feast, always has the chance to summon two of it and a Sjette or one of it and Seistema, in conclusion two of one mill on top of this action. Reason 4, Decatron gains the effect of any infernoid; that's awesome!!    Sjette and Attondel are here because I like them and they are good targets for Void Feast. That 's all.   Seistema is strong for no reason. If it attacks it can banish a card without targeting at the end of the battle phase.     Onuncu and Devyaty, the big Bosses. Onuncu is a dark hole on legs that negates and banishes spells/traps . Deviaty is a heavy storm on legs that negates and banishes monster’s effects.   Tierra is the target for performing fusing using Void Imagination . Only in the process to summon it, the advantage gained is colossal because it is an instant mill of 6 infernoids . When she hits the field, her effect will gain even more advantage: mill 3 extra deck and top deck’s cards for each player (your opponent loses combo pieces and you can mill Psy- Framelord Omega, Wind Pegasus @Ignister or Elder Entity N'Tss) .   Tools to set the world on fire    Void Vanishment is the search for any other void card and a set up for the Void Feast.   Void Feast is a really cool tool, because If you have two of it and another void trap/spell, you could activate the fist one to send a void trap/spell to the Gy and activate the second send the fist Void Feast, getting the two of them resolving.   Void Imagination lowers the level of every infernoid to one  with the downside that your opponent will receive half of damage. With that you can continue summon infernoids without worrying about the total level count on the field. However,the real good use is to summon Tierra from your extra deck using 6 monsters from your deck, if your opponent controls a monster special summoned from the extra deck. That’s a set up, follow up and a body with a lot of effects on the field.   Void apocalipse is a good card to set up your GY with infernoids that you may need.   The fire is good, but I thing it’s missing some Darkness   The lair of Darkness package is here to give the cost of any infernoid to the opponent. The Field spell itself is for that, bypassing even dragoon protection. Ahrima is here to search the field spell and to possibly bring the Diabolos, a very good monster to deal with. Beat Cop is here to tribute an opponent’s monsters and give protection to the field spell.   Psych tricks and magic tricks are also good    The PSY-Framegear Gamma package is here to give a chance to interrupt your opponent in his turn without breaking the consistency with reasoning and monster gate. Also PSY-Framelord Omega can be used in rare synchro plays and with Tierra, if he gets milled.   Reasoning and Monster Gate are here to mill the deck, only. One for one, bring fast the Decatron. And the Pot of Extravagance is a pot of greed in this deck.   For the extra deck,staring:   Wee Witch's Apprentice and Duelittle Chimera to give that little atack boost for an otk.   Crusadia Equimax for a big beat stick.   Gravity Controller is a fun one. With Tierra on the field, because it’s level is 11 your play with infernoid should stop right there, but with him, won’t. That’s because Tierra  can be used as material to summon him, leaving the level count on the field equal zero.   Wind Pegasus @Ignister and Elder Entity N'Tss can be sent to GY by Tierra. There Elder Entity N'Tss can destroy what you want and Wind Pegasus @Ignistertarget  can  target 1 card your opponent controls; shuffle it into the Deck if any monster gets destroyed.   Relinquished Anima can steal one of your opponent's monsters if Deactron gets negated but not destroyed.    The side   Generic to deal with anything. Spell/traps, big fields and give even more interruptions.

deck_excerpt: Small, fluffy pastel animals are cute and all, but become an unstoppable armageddon of death with the right tools and support at their disposal.
deck_description: This deck performed leagues better than I ever expected it to, since it started as a build I found on YGOPro myself and modified into the powerhouse it is now (Shoutout to the original legend here) - https://ygoprodeck.com/a-budget-way-for-a-melffy-day/ MONSTERS For the meat of the deck, Melffys, the three best for this build are Fennec, Puppy, and Catty. By returning to your hand on an opponent's summon or battle declaration, Fennec allows you to special summon a Beast from the hand, Puppy allows you to special summon a Level 2 Beast from the deck, and Catty allows you to add a Beast to your hand from the deck. Overall, these three have the best main-deck synergy and open up the board to the other combos of the deck. Ponpoko is a great lead into Tantan, who can special summon Kalantosa, which when special summoned by a Beast, it can destroy any card on the field. This makes Kalantosa the main-deck's carry to maintain board. Additionally, Valerifawn has the ability to special summon Kalantosa from the GY (proccing effect), and leading into, at lowest, level 4 synchro plays. Alpha is also a good emergency monster for when the opponent has board, between being able to special summon from hand if your opponent has a higher total attack point value (which is common since Melffys have the attacking power of a wet napkin), and being able to send Beasts from the field back to the hand to send face-up monsters on your opponent's field to their hand (which is good for clearing extra deck summons). To top it off, Barrier Statue of the Drought is a safety net to keep your opponent from building a non-Earth board for as long as possible.   SPELLS Most importantly, Obedience Schooled is ideal in a starting hand, first or second. Special summons three Level 2 or lower Beasts from the deck to the field, with the drawback of their effects being negated and only being able to summon Beasts for the rest of the turn (which is good for this deck, since extra deck plays are the build's extenders and carry). Equally important, Hide-and-Seek, which prevents card effect destruction once per turn and can shuffle three Beasts with different names from the GY to the deck, then drawing one card afterwards. Next, Child's Play is incredible in a combo-heavy meta and, if your opponent goes nuts, 10,000 life points is easy to achieve to prevent your monsters from being destroyed by battle, and Foolish Burial is included for the sake of getting Kalantosa to the GY easily to pave the way for Valerifawn. For control, Twin Twisters and Harpie's Feather Duster are solid means of keeping backrow in check.   TRAPS Mirror Force. Less is more.   EXTRA DECK Melffy Mommy and Melffy of the Forest are essential to keep this deck well-oiled. Ideally, with starting hand including Obedience Schooled, going OS into Melffy of the Forest is the go-to first play. Then, if Hide-and-Seek isn't in the starting hand, using Forest's effect to get it is the next move. Play H&S, and if there's another Level 2 monster in your starting hand, you could always use it and the other monster summoned by OS to start Mommy, who at 5 materials becomes the ultimate attacker for the deck. Mommy has three stages; at 3 materials, she cannot be destroyed by battle. At 4, you take no battle damage from battles involving her. at 5, any attack position monster she's included in a battle against (whether she's in attack or defense position), her effect deals damage to your opponent equal to the opponent's monster's attack. This is the deck's boss monster and win condition, if successfully protected by H&S and Mirror Force. Secondarily, Number 64 is good for challenging heavy boards due to its ability to summon tokens with attack equal to the highest attack on the field, and Marjoram alongside Child's Play is a good way to clear cards on the field (once per turn) if Kalantosa isn't an option. Dark Mist is included for grins, but can come in handy in tight spots, as well as the other synchro monsters included in this build.
