deck_excerpt: Pure Evil★Twin/Live☆Twin with a bunch of HT
deck_description: Cutting Ki-sikil was never a mistake, and i never regret it.. But.. But.. deck consistency.. Listen here, consistency was the least thing this deck worries about. You need more extender, not more normal summon..

Alright I was not gonna make another update for the deck until new support arrives, but seeing my old list being the most viewed Dragonmaid list while being still based on Elpy/ including it is something I dont feel to good about, so I am gonna send through my updated list now. Basically we try and keep it really similiar, just adding a few more fusion target, a new side play for heavenly sphere and thats mostly it. The most important thing is, that we are not aiming for five head dragon + 1-2 negates anymore. We rather try to set up follow up turns where we explode and sheer force our self over the opponents board, or grind them turn by turn out. Lets go over it card by card and talk about the goal we have with this deck. The dragonmaid core : 3 Chamber : Searches you the fusion spell, hospi to extend, tidying to extend if you have ravine or to set for controll. She is one of the 1 card sphere maker and what is really important, she is the only one able to summon the fusion maids from grave at the start of the bp. 3 Parlor : Basically works the same as chamber and does almost all the same. Only difference she can send tidying directly for combo, but cant gets its controll eff. However if you already have extender in hand she is a good way to get nurse or any other maid you may need later to grave. Also a 1 card sphere 1 Nurse : She is one of the cards holding the deck together. Overworked nurses are sadly also part in a fantasy card game, thats why you want to use her every turn to extend and summon more maids. She is basically a flat +1 or +2 everytime you summon her ones the grave is set. 1 Changeover : Your fusion spell to go into the gem of the deck Dragonmaid Sheou/Strahl or House in rare cases. Important to remember for the gy effect, even if the target leaves the board, you still add changeover to hand. 2 Hospitality : Probably one of the most broken extender to ever be printed. Set up your grave, non target summon from hand and gy. Searchable and one activation a turn no use. Sadly the price tag is justified, but dont buy it if you can avoid. Dont let people sky rock the price and gate people out. the reprint is coming ! 3 Tidiyng : Looping cards back to hand and in best case triggering your House is always good, but non target summon from hand or gy in etiher players turn while being searchable by two cards ? This card should be the 40$ one~ Also REMEMBER the targets once targeted dont need to stay on board to resolve. You can tar sphere, chain sphere and bounce 2 cards. 1 Dragonmaid Ernus : Can summon a maid in your opponents turn before they set up the negats , else just for its name and level 1 Dragonmaid Lorpar : Name and Level again. But its also a decent card to force a negate with its discard effect.   Rokket : 2 Tracer : Its tracer, it summons another rokket for a free  Savage Dragon, and can be summoned by quick launch. Yeah, I dont know how quick launch and this can exist at the same time. Also its a 1 card I:P , allows you to do guardragon through hand traps and is always a combo saver / extender / starter. 1 Absoruter : As we play Ravine we love discarding things that also give us free cards back so this card is already good for us, but it can also work as a mini noctovision dragon if we have a rokket on board. Dragon, free summon and search? Sign me up 1 Silver : Wont come up often but the banish eff can be nice. ( Update : after maybe 100 games, the banish eff still never came up. Still a different name so we keep it) 1 Recharger : target for quicklaunch and tracer, but also can work with striker dragon eff to recycle a tracer back to hand and summon 2 of boot sector
  1. Boot Sector : Summon striker, search this spam rokkets. Simple
  2.  3x Quick Launch : Not once per turn free rokket Monster
Dragons : 2 Noctovision : Make striker = free summon. Simple. gives you a extra draw and protects your set tidying when in grave, this card is basically a dragonmaid. Since its release its been probably the most played card which isnt part of the archtype. 2 Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay : With Sky Striker and other link decks running around, its just a nice card to have, also it fixed goddess weakness of being targeted + its a high level dragon to fusion. Also it lets you dig for super poly and other cards which may save your day when the opponent starts playing solitair. Also it annoys sky striker and we love to do that 1 Dragons Ravine : Search of Romulus and dumb extender and send extender. Or send Gram for another big body. Also cleans your hand of cards you dont want to have there 1 Tempest 1 Gold Sako : Simple combo to search  Parlor or....well there is only Parlor left. Maybe Lorpar in rare cases? 1 Fallen of Albaz : You summon him of Sphere most of the time and just poly away their boss Monster for a titanclad, its a easy dragoon out, as if they negate sphere bounce you just summon him and fusion dragoon away. Its probably my favorite non maid in this deck. ALSO we have a new combo for him, I will explain later. Hand traps : 3 Ash + Super poly/ Lancea . Super poly is king in this deck as we can also use it during the BP to get a bit more damage on board, while it also just ruins dragonlinks day, and annoys shadoll / invoked to no compare. 2 Ghost Bell : With Tri bri, Sky Striker and Drytron running around this card became much more important again. Specially as it can negate tri bri revolution which is usally the end of the game for them Extra : 1x Dragonmaid Sheou : Its your best card, its your free summon omni negate, waifu, dragon. Also we play only one because she shuffels herself back. 2x House Dragonmaid : So we can use Sheou omni negate, or pop a whole opponents board. We can shuffel her back and usually dont need more 1x Borrel Savage : Omni negate, whats to say. Sadly not a maid 1x Titanclad the Ashdragon : Summon of Albaz to remove a boss monster or if its send by maximus to get you a free albaz to combo with / fusion into venom dragon 1x Starving Venom Dragon : Its a awesome super poly / fallen of Albaz target. While also a threat to the board right after being summoned. 1x Romulus : Searches Dragon Ravine for you and is a good link 2 target with good zones 1x Pitsy  : The extender dragon which is the last link guardragon not banned YET.  Its a link 1 dragon we can summon to extend and can still use zones of goddess and five head. But dont force a summon with it without the 2. Its rarely worth it 2x Sphere : One of the stronges interrupts in the game + free summon from deck + good zones + being a dragon + 1 card out to dragoon. And can make any light based deck go -3. Will explain that combo in the side deck 1x Mudragon : Super poly target , also the target protection is lovely against sky striker 1x Striker Dragon : link 1. dragon. searches boot sector launch. the only thing this thing misses is a it pointing downwards 1x Underworld Goddess of the Closed World : The new card we try to abuse, or atleast flex with. We usually will always summon her with I:p but its not to hard  summon her with all the dragons and maids rotating at all times. She also doesnt care about DRM and all the annoying things being played. Laughing at Dragoon with her only being outed in battle 1x Link God Dragon/ Fiveheaded Link Dragon : We want to make him almost every turn, as your opponent will 99,99% not play anything that can out this thing. You will have a full grave for atleast 3-4 turns were you could just sit on it , but as you play maids, you will just combo again and again with a 5k beater who cant be stopped. Side deck : Its really up to you what you play in here but this combo I wanna showcase 1x Albion fusion dragon : 1 x Rokket fusion dragon : The combo is basically to use sphere to bounce a card of your opponent (-1) summon Fallen of Albus and fusion it with a n opponents light monster into Albion (-2) , summon with Albion Rokket fusion and pop another card with its effect (-3) All in all this deck is just learning which card leads to which combo, but the end board you should aim for is usually Sphere + Sheou or ones you know the cards a little better you can end on more. But keeping a few hand traps, traps is currently better. Afterwords : I am happy with how this deck developed over the past months and I think it was close to being as good as this version can be. However the elpy bann really weakend it sadly, more than anyone expacted. The deck rewards you for making decisions in either players turn while also having straight goals which you play towards. But in the end the best part of this deck is, having your opponents scoop instantly after playing five head / no fully realizing how immun it is / not wanting to belive what they read for a moment, while than seeing that they are now on the glock to out this thing or lose. I think in all my games only 1-2 Persons were able to win after it was summoned. One was just stalling until I ran out of cards to banish other was a Kaiju top deck. So its still a good average of staying and winning you the game.   And thats my new crap guide to Dragonmaid, you welcome.

deck_excerpt: A Aggro deck that can swarm the field and go into XYZ and Link plays going 2nd or 1st, Combos. R8NK DECK
deck_description:
Possible end boards

Divine Dragon Knight Felgrand + Number 68: Sanaphond the Sky Prison + I:P  Masquerena That go into Knightmare Unicorn ( Can discard Dangers!) or Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess+ Number 97:Draglubion and Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy + Evilswarm Nightmare.

Tour Guide From the Underworld

She can summon Sangan to go into Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss so that you can search with Sangan Santa Claws (Can still be used because Sangan does not restrict Special Summoning the monster) and send Gokipole with Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss to search Danger! Mothman!. Tour Guide From the Underworld can also Special Summon Doomdog Octhros to search Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World but i find it more viable to search Santa Claws. Plus you have Salamangreat Almiraj in case you open with either Gokipole/Doomdog Octhros/Sangan. Tour Guide From the Underworld can also Special summon Broww, Huntsman of Dark World so that you can bring back Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World from grave.

Basically

It's a deck to destroy boards and either finish the game in one turn thanks to high attack monsters such as Number 100: Numeron Dragon or go into Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star, to rank-up into Number 84: Pain Gainer, and overlay for Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder To get a Double activation on it. It's a Deck that can perform well going second and going first, because it as to be good going first since your opennent will let you go first since it's a deck that can easely OTK so that's why i try to give it a Combo-ish style that can still end on negates and interruptions

Cool Stuff

Number 97: Draglubion says that you cannot attack except with the monster you summon by it's effect, but if Divine Dragon Knight Felgrand activates it's effect and targets another monster you control, it will not be affected by the restriction of Number 97: Draglubion and will be still able to attack. You can use Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World as XYZ Material for Divine Dragon Knight Felgrand and immediatly activates it's effect to negate itself so that you can detach Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World and bring him back later. You can also play cards such as Gizmek Orochi, the Serpentron Sky Slasher, Shaddoll Beast, Performage Trick Clown,Number 23: Lancelot, Dark Knight of the Underworld (For better Zeus access and additional negates because even if it's effect is mandatory, the effect doesn't destroy and since Dangers! will get negated and not destroyed it'll still will be able to activate it's effects but for reasons i decide to go for Dingirsu since he's more usefull and outs dragoon because the Extradeck is Thight) and Curious, the Lightsworn Dominion. You can also play Crusadia Draco for going first since Sangan can search it instead of Santa Claws so that you turbo out Dugares faster.

deck_excerpt: A dedicated Winged Dragon of Ra deck that can hold its own competitively.
deck_description:
Great beast of the sky, please hear my cry--

Transform thyself from orb of light and bring me victory in this fight--

Envelop the desert with your glow and cast your rage upon my foe--

Unlock your powers from deep within so that together we may win--

Appear in this shadow game as I call your name--

Winged Dragon of Ra!

In September 2020, The Winged Dragon of Ra received a great deal of support in the form of Legendary Duelists 7: Rage of Ra. Now, with the proper support, the monster that was supposed to be the greatest of the Egyptian Gods can wreak its fiery devastation across decks of every tier level.
The Winged Dragon of Ra was always my favorite card in the whole game. Now I finally get to play him the way he deserves to be played. I've been fine-tuning this deck for months, and this build allows me to play Ra as the untouchable, omnipotent god he was always meant to be.
Here's a card-by-card breakdown of all the excellent support cards Rage of Ra provided, and the most efficient applications of each.
 
Ancient Chant searches Ra, from either deck or graveyard, graveyard being relevant every now and then (more on that later). It also grants you one extra summon, and gives Ra the power to absorb the ATK/DEF of the monsters tributed to summon him. These are all self-evidently great effects that don't need much examination, but here are a few general notes about making the most of this spell:
1. Just playing the card gives you an extra tribute summon. You have to remember to banish it from your graveyard before performing the tribute summon if you want Ra to gain the tributes' ATK. On that note, Soul Crossing lets you sacrifice your opponent's monsters for a Divine monster (like Ra!). Soul Crossing is a Quick-Play spell, and that's obviously awesome, but if you play it as a normal spell on your turn, you can banish Ancient Chant from your graveyard first, and Ra will absorb your opponent's monsters' ATK points. This can lead to some interesting variations on Ra's ATK, since the only monsters of your own you'll ever really be sacrificing are Reactor Slime and its two slime tokens for 1500 base ATK points, or Egyptian God Slime for 3000. Of course, that base ATK is in addition to the life points you can then pay to Ra's ATK.
2. On rare occasions, you might find yourself in a situation where all three copies of Ra are in the graveyard, and you have the Sphere Mode of Ra in play. Sphere Mode only searches Ra from hand or deck. Ancient Chant can put Ra back into your hand from the graveyard in this instance, letting you activate an otherwise useless Sphere Mode.
 
Blaze Cannon is the card that turns Ra into the all-powerful, game-warping god that he was in the anime. It is a quick-play spell that can't be negated, and it grants Ra three effects for one turn:
1. Ra is unaffected by your opponent's cards' effects
2. When Ra battles, you can tribute any number of other monsters that did not declare attacks this turn and add their ATK points to Ra until the end of the turn
3. After damage calculation, if Ra attacked, send all monsters your opponent controls to the graveyard.
The applications of this card are even more straightforward than Ancient Chant's. Play it when you are ready to end the game with Ra, or set it and use it as a trap to save Ra from anything your opponent might try to use against your Divine Beast.
 
Guardian Slime is the goo that holds this deck together. You can special summon it when you take any kind of damage, and its DEF rises to match the ATK of the first monster to attack it.
But the real value of Guardian Slime is its search effect. When sent to the graveyard from either your field or your hand, you can add any Spell or Trap that mentions The Winged Dragon of Ra in its text from your deck to your hand. This is really the card that lets you reliably summon, protect, and reform Ra (more on that later) as the situation requires.  
 
Dark Spell Regeneration is an interesting card, tricky and deceptively powerful. Its steal-a-spell effect is... fun, but most spells in the game at this point are hyper-specific to the deck running them, and won't help you much outside of that deck. Unless you actually see a generically useful spell in their graveyard (like Monster Reborn, the card that Dark Spell Regeneration was obviously designed to steal), you are better off just discarding this fascinating Trap card, setting up its powerful removal-resurrection trick.
More on that later...
 
Millennium Revelation is a flexible card with wide-reaching applications. It lets you discard a Divine monster to search Monster Reborn, from deck or graveyard. The most obvious thing you can do with it is trade Ra for Monster Reborn, and then resurrect Ra, even though the very first line of text on The Winged Dragon of Ra is, "This monster cannot be Special Summoned," Millennium Revelation allows you to do so anyway, "ignoring its summoning conditions." Ra will have 0 ATK, but he can still destroy any monster for 1000 of your LP.  Millennium Revelation also combos very well with the all the other Ra support cards I'm going to go over, including Dark Spell Regeneration, but especially--
 
Sun God Unification lets you move your Life Points to and from Ra at will. It is the answer to the problem of summoning Ra with 0 ATK, and is the key to the single most powerful trick of which the deck is capable. Its actual effects are:
1. You can pay Life Points until you have 100 left, one Special Summoned (only if it was Special Summoned) The Winged Dragon of Ra gains ATK points equal to the amount of Life Points paid
2. You can tribute The Winged Dragon of Ra; gain Life Points equal to Ra's ATK.
 
Sun God Unification and Millennium Revelation Millennium Revelation are a match made in heaven. Discard Ra, search Monster Reborn, resurrect Ra, feed him all your Life Points but 100, and attack for whatever absurdly huge number that may be. THEN, Tribute Ra and resorb all those Life Points, since Millennium Revelation requires Ra to return to the graveyard at the end of the turn in which he was Special Summoned this way.
 
If you have managed to put Dark Spell Regeneration into the graveyard, now is the time to remind your opponent of that fact. If you have a copy of Ra in the graveyard and Monster Reborn in hand (which is exactly what you'll have if you've just used Millennium Revelation), Dark Spell Regeneration's in-graveyard-activation requirements are met. Banish Dark Spell Regeneration, discard Monster Reborn, and Ra will return to the field, while at the same time sending one of your opponent's monsters to the graveyard (not targeting, not destroying). From that point, you can use Sun God Unification as outlined above.
 
On the subject of Ra going to the graveyard, now is the time to talk about the fact that Ra is set apart from his fellow gods Slifer and Obelisk in that Ra is the only Egyptian God with multiple forms. The Winged Dragon of Ra - Immortal Phoenix is a monster with 4000 ATK and DEF that is completely immune to any and all effects. It can only be summoned if it was in the graveyard while The Winged Dragon of Ra went from the field to the graveyard. If you have managed to put the Phoenix in the graveyard before launching the Millennium Revelation/ Sun God Unification combo, you can resurrect Ra, attack for, let's say, 7900, and then tribute Ra still during the Battle Phase to unleash the Phoenix, repleting your Life Points and piling on another 4000 points' worth of damage. Attacking with Ra and then with the Phoenix is unexpected and devastating, and is probably the most powerful maneuver of which the deck is capable.
The Winged Dragon of Ra - Immortal Phoenix also has a much stronger monster-clearing effect: for 1000 Life Points, you can send any one monster on the field to the graveyard, without targeting or destroying it, and you can use it as many times in a row as you can afford.
Immune to everything, capable of incinerating anything, regardless of their protection, the Phoenix has only one weakness: it must return to the graveyard at the end of the turn in which it was summoned. At this point, you search your hand, deck, or graveyard for the third form of Ra: Sphere Mode. 
The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode cannot be attacked or targeted. You can tribute it to Special Summon The Winged Dragon of Ra from your hand or deck (not graveyard), ignoring Ra's summoning conditions (cannot be Special Summoned), and granting Ra a base ATK and DEF of 4000. Since this is one of the only other ways to Special Summon Ra, Sun God Unification and the Sphere Mode of Ra is another match made in heaven. Use the Sphere to summon Ra with 4000 ATK, add 7900 with Sun God Unification, attack for 11,900, tribute Ra (for a net gain of 4000 Life Points, by the way), and then unleash the Phoenix to add another 4000 damage.
 
This is the ideal way to play Ra, looping him in and out of his three forms to completely overwhelm your opponent.
 
This requires a little set-up, namely, getting the Phoenix into the graveyard in the first place. Before the card The True Sun God was released in September of 2022's Tin of the Pharaoh's Gods, this was considerably more difficult. There was no way to search the Phoenix, barring bizarre cards like Card of the Soul, or Extra Deck monsters whose materials we aren't running. You had to either send it straight to the GY with Foolish Burial, which is of course a one-of, or happen to draw the Phoenix so you could discard it with something like Millennium Revelation or Forbidden Droplet. It was the deck's greatest weakness; so many times I thought to myself, all we need now is a way to search the Phoenix, and this deck will truly be a force to be reckoned with.
 
And now, we have The True Sun God: a universal searcher for anything that says The Winged Dragon of Ra anywhere on it, that also lets you trade an on-field Winged Dragon for an in-deck Immortal Phoenix. And also says monsters (besides Ra) can't attack in the same turn they were special summoned for some reason. 
 
While this card is obviously awesome, here are a few notes about using it to its full potential:
 
I usually use its first effect to search the Phoenix right away, and then I find my own way to discard it. What I really want is to be able to attack with Ra, sacrifice it to Sun God Unification during the Battle Phase, and then attack again with the Phoenix. It's nice that the card gives you the power to summon the Phoenix on its own, but if you use this option, you will miss out on the double attack opportunity.
 
There is an interesting little floodgate effect in the middle there, about how Special Summoned monsters (except The Winged Dragon of Ra) can't attack the turn they are summoned (the Immortal Phoenix can also attack the turn it was summoned, because it is unaffected by other cards' effects). This is presumably a reference to Ra's ill-defined "Instant Attack" power in the anime, an ability that allowed Ra to attack in the same turn it was summoned—an ability that all monsters already have. It let Marik play around Vengeful Bog Spirit that one time, I guess, but in subsequent duels, he would summon Ra and then announce that he was using the power of "Instant Attack" to attack right away, in the total absence of any reason he wouldn't have been able to anyway... Kaiba, too, was inexplicably impressed when he translated and read this useless ability, but I guess that is all besides the point. The point is, this slightly bewildering line of text is extremely easy to forget, and if you're playing paper, you will have to remind your opponent they can't attack you with monsters that were just special summoned, which they will inevitably try to do, probably repeatedly. You might sometimes have occasion to attack with Egyptian God Slime, but he is also held back by The True Sun God (so just feed him to Ra with Blaze Cannon.)
 
The True Sun God is the final piece of the puzzle, and now that it is here, the deck is more consistent and powerful than ever. In fact, after trying to make the deck work without it, it almost makes everything too easy...
 
The Winged Dragon of Ra is, occasionally, dismissed by the ignorant and short-sighted as the weakest of the Egyptian Gods. This is simply untrue; the confusing design of Ra, with its "?" ATK and it seemingly self-contradicting abilities is a puzzle to be solved, a test to ensure that only those who truly understand Ra can wield him successfully, a test which most duelists fail. Just like in the anime, if you wish to wield the power of the most supreme Egyptian God, you have to prove yourself worthy first. And only a chosen few will succeed in this. By following this guide, you can be one of these few.
 
This is the Day of Wrath.

This is a dracoslayer deck built by yours truly, it acts a lot more like a supreme king deck but I built it with dracoslayer in mind.

Overall I made it based around destruction. My card list and reasonings are below

3 revolution dragon, revolution dragon is a 3 of in any dragon reliant pendulum deck, and dracoslayer is definitely no exception. This card gives you access to luster pendulum which is absolutely vital in this deck, so it is at 3 and stays at 3

1 zero, the darkwurm search

1 lector pendulum, for the name for face off

1 master pendulum, one if the shrine mills, I’ll explain later

3 luster pendulum, Star of the show, absolutely vital to have at 3 in dracoslayers as it’s their only tuner

1 vector pendulum, another name

3 darkwurm, darkwurm is just a good card in general, I couldn’t refuse it tbh

1 skullcrowbat joker, it came back! I used to not think anything of it’s return but now that I learned of how well it works in dracoslayer I changed my mind, it searches revolution dragon who in turn searches luster pendulum, plus it a level 4 pendulum, I’d play 3 if possible tbh.

1 black fang, for my small magician engine

2 double iris, I mean, star pendulumgraph is useful plus it just got out of the banlist so I may as well as get it some use, right?

1 celestial magician, provides two namesakes and a end phase search for the grind so it go’s a slot.

3 pendulum sorcerer, one of the ace cards searching skullcrobat joker and celestial magician, and triggering destruction effects, not bad.

2 hexasaucer, a little tech I thought up of, hexasaucer is the closest I have at the moment to plushfire, so I took it.

3 harmonizing, summoning free synchros sense the pendulum era

1 Star pendulumgraph, search for iris, floats your cards

3 dragon shrine, for dumping master pendulum and darkwurm, the idea of dumping pendulum is because dinoster summons from the graveyard

3 duelist alliance, allowing you to search any dracoslayer or dracoverlord, they’re all pendulum cards!

3 pendulum call, im playing enough pendulum magicians that it would be wrong not to play it, right?

1 draco face-off, setup for play, wish it was at 3

3 infinite impenitence, for the sake of having something to do on their turn

1 starving venom, gateway zero summon

1 dinoster power, as an extender and protection

3 ignister prominence, easily one of my favorite cards of all time, prominence is a deck summoner and boss in one.

1 supreme king dragon clear wing, another boss

1 number 38, with all of these level 8 dragons I just decided to play it

1 arc rebellion, a seriously powerful way to push for game, I love it

1 supreme king dragon dark rebellion, namesake, extender, and beatstick that can sometimes turn a game around if your opponents monster is big enough

1 timestar, literally only there because it searches, protection is just an added bonus

1 raider’s knight, how else would you summon arc rebellion? It’s what makes it work!

2 ascending dracoslayer, extender, look below

1 draco future, because the ascending dracoslayer searches on its end phase and then gives you a monster that can help you summon a different dracoslayer which summons a dracoslayer monster to help you get another ascending dracoslayer you can do that chain for a utopic future, it’s complex but effective

1 utopic future, to get dragon, why not?

The deck is really weird and is entirely wing it

Strong points:

This deck is really good at recursion and really resilient with all of the floating

There are tons of searchers and lots of card advantage, it’s really hard to open a hand so bad you can’t do anything, you’ll always have something in the end if you go uninterrupted (which is unlikely but most of the time you can even go interrupted)

If you’re opponent is in the advantage you can suddenly surprise them with some super unexpected and sometimes stupid stuff like “arc rebellion shake”

Weak points

The pendulum mechanic sucks at times

You always want to start off with getting luster pendulum out, this can lead to some easy turn ending negates at times

Droll is an absolute pain for this deck

deck_excerpt: Purely made for fun play. The Twin of my other Rose-themed deck "World of Roses".
deck_description:
Death offers you thorns, eternity offers you roses, and life offers you both.
There is only one thing in YuGiOh! that I love as much as I love Cyber Dragons: Rose Dragons! The Rose Dragon archetype to me has always been a cool concept, Dragons and Roses combined, centered around Synchro summoning. The archetype features one of the most beautiful set of artworks in my eyes. However, the Rose Dragons have never been a really consistent or all around strong archetype. There was always something missing, an important part that somehow got lost. Until now. With the release of Lightning Overdrive, the deck got all the cards it needed so desperately. "Basal Rose Shoot" for example, is a wonderful spell to make the effect of "Black Rose Dragon" change from an all-in suicide bomb into a black hole with self protection. The archetype also got a new field spell with "White Rose Cloister". Nothing crazy but it shouldn't be underestimated. Anyways, let's get to the "how-to-use" section of this page. It's actually really not that hard, not that special. The heart of the deck are the Rose Dragonlings. "White Rose Dragon" and "Blue Rose Dragon" are your LVL 4 non-tuners while "Red Rose Dragon" as well as "Roxrose Dragon" are your LVL 3 tuner monsters, which you will be use mainly to summon your Boss monsters like "Black Rose Dragon" and "Black Rose Moonlight Dragon" as well as "Ruddy Rose Dragon". To keep a good 50:50 between Dragon type monsters and monsters of a different type is important to get "Crossrose Dragon" out more easily, which then goes into your Synchros without the need to fulfill its LVL requirements. You basicly go around the whole process of Synchro summoning via adding up the monsters levels to each others, basicly call it "Alternative Synchro Summoning". "Rose Princess", altho not being a tuner, can act as one as well if you summon her with her effect. Otherwise, if you don't already have it, you use her to search out "White Rose Cloister" as this helps you to easily bring out a tuner and a non-tuner (or simply two monsters) in one turn, by allowing you to special summon a Rose Dragonling or a plant type monster from your hand in case you don't control any monsters but your opponent does. It also helps you buff your LVL 7 Dragon Synchros for a whole 1000 ATK if you make a right guess at the beginning of your turn. Via "Ruddy Rose Witch", you can even put a plant-type monster on top of your deck, to make the guess for the next turn a 100% right one. The 50:50 in therms of monster types also lets you use "Frozen Rose" more effectively if you are willing to make a little sacrifice. Once you got your Rose-Synchro Boss monsters out, you can protect them more easily with your trap cards. "Blooming of the Darkest Rose" lets your Black Rose Dragon "dodge" a fatal blow/effect from your opponent, while "Shadow Impulse" lets you swap your Synchro monsters, in case your opponent destroy one of them. This works with Black Rose Dragon -> Black Rose Moonlight Dragon and vice versa as well as Ruddy Rose Dragon -> "Ascension Sky Dragon" and vice versa which leaves you at least not completely open, if your opponent gets over your Synchros. "Synchro Transmission" however lets you place a trap for your opponent to easily wipe the whole board before he ends his Main Phase if you use it to summon a Black Rose Dragon, as well as giving you a nice little extra card in your next turn, by sending your Black Rose Dragon back to your Extra Deck. All around I really gotta say that Lightning Overdrive definetely brought some new delicious stuff to this archetype, mostly with its brand new Boss monster; the Ruddy Rose Dragon; as well as with the spell card Basal Rose Shoot. Thanks to Roxrose Dragon, it's almost laughably easy to bring out a Black Rose Dragon which then immediately goes into its new, stronger variant. If you are interested in more Rose-themed/plant themed decks or if you are simply a fan of Akiza, I recommend you to check out my other deck profile: "World of Roses"   Discord: Lucy💗🌺🦋#1508 Reddit Steam
https://youtu.be/G4nQB5_k4G0

deck_name: Triple SD Challenge - Egyptian God Slifer
deck_description:
Today, as a part of my Triple Structure Deck Challenge series, I decided this time to build 2 decks based around the Egyptian God Deck: Slifer the Sky Dragon and Egyptian God Deck: Obelisk the Tormentor; starting with Slifer.  (Both decks will be uploaded).  The rules are the same, the Main Deck must be strictly a 40-card deck with 30 or more cards being from the Egyptian God Deck: Slifer the Sky Dragon Structure Deck. The Extra Deck can use any cards you want to. Starting by explaining the star of the deck, Slifer the Sky Dragon (& Executive Producer) is a Level 10 DIVINE Divine-Beast monster with ? Atk/? Def. He, alongside Obelisk & Ra share the same summoning condition that requires a Tribute Summon of 3 monsters and when Summoned, neither player can activate cards or effects. Slifer unique effects are that its gains 1000 Atk/Def for each card in your hand; if your opponent Normal or Special Summons one or more monsters, all of those monsters loses 2000 Atk/Def and if its Atk becomes 0 by this effect, they are immediately destroyed; also, if it was Special Summoned instead of Tribute Summoned, it sends itself to the GY at the End Phase of that turn. A very iconic boss monster that, in my opinion, has of the most strongest floodgate effects if your opponent cant get rid of it. Both Slifer and Obelisk recieved new support cards in order to favor their playstyle, as well as making them a bit easier to summon and what legacy support would exist without making them cards that represent their signature attacks in the anime? Since this is the Slifer deck, we'll start with his signature card, Thunderforce Attack. Is a Quick-Play Spell that can only be activated while you control AN ORIGINAL Slifer the Sky Dragon; it allows you to destroy as many face-up monsters your opponent controls. After that, it gives you the choice of drawing cards equal to the number of destroyed monsters that were sent to the opponent's GY (this is to prevent the player to place your own monsters or tokens and then blow them up), but if you do, you can only declare 1 attack for the rest of the turn. It can act as a Quick-Play Raigeki while also being a +1/+2 in the most common scenarios, however it can be bricky and requires setup. Playing it at 3 can be risky, so I recommend playing 2. Next is another Quick-Play Spell, Soul Crossing. During the Main Phase, immediately after the effect resolves, you can Tribute Summon a Divine-Beast monster by tributing any 3 monsters on the field, including your opponents (by the way, yes, you can use up to 3 of your opponents' monsters). If you used at least 1 monster that belongs to your opponent, you can only activate 1 card effect for the rest of the turn, but the effects of Divine-Beast monsters are excluded from this effect lock. Unless your opponent negates this card effect, this is card is a non-target, non-destruction removal of 1 to 3 of their monsters, while also giving you a free monster. This is a safe 3 of, and also allows to play 3 copies of Slifer since it can prevent it from being a brick in your hand. The last new support card that I used from the deck is Ultimate Divine-Beast, a Continuous Trap. If your opponent declares an attack, you can discard 1 Spell/Trap to Special Summon a Divine-Beast monster from the GY in Defense Position and then it redirects the attack to itself. During the End Phase: if you control a Divine-Beast monster, you can destroy all face-up cards your opponent controls that activated their effect this turn. While it can be a bit costly to activate, it has good effects and yes, you can activate the second effect before Slifer goes back to the GY. The deck also includes Tellus the Little Angel and Millenium Seeker as support cards, but this build will not use them. As a quick explanation, Tellus the Little Angel is a token generator that works from the GY, and Millenium Seeker can Special Summon itself for the hand but it has a very double-edged effect. And now, the outside support:
  • Level 10 Slimes (*sad train noises*): This Structure Deck features Reactor Slime and Metal Reflect Slime. Reactor Slime, during the Main Phase, can Special Summon 2 tokens, but locks you on only summoning Divine-Beast monsters for the rest of the turn; and during the Battle Phase, as a Quick Effect, can send itself to the GY to set a Metal Reflect Slime from your hand, Deck or GY and it can be activated that turn (which is a Continuous Trap that Special Summons itself as a Level 10 WATER Aqua monster with 0 Atk/3000 Def). In order to have the full engine, I added 3 copies of Guardian Slime and Egyptian God Slime. Guardian Slime is a Level 10 WATER Aqua monster with 0 Atk/Def that can Special Summon itself from the hand if you take battle or effect damage. During damage calculation, it can make its Def equal to an attacking monsters' Atk. If it is sent to the GY from the hand or field, it can search any Spell/Trap that enlists "The Winged Dragon of Ra" on its text. On the other hand, Egyptian God Slime is a Level 10 WATER Aqua Fusion monster with 3000 Atk/Def that can also be Special Summoned by Tributing 1 Level 10 Aqua monster with 0 Atk. It cannot be destroyed by battle, your opponent can only target this card for both attacks and effects and it can be treated as 3 tributes for a Tribute Summon. Both cards are very reliable and grants a lot of protection to the deck while paired with...
  • Mound of the Bound Creator: A Field Spell that makes Level 10 or higher monsters unable to be destroyed or targeted by card effects, if they destroy a monster by battle it burns the opponent for 1000 and if it is destroyed, you can add 1 DIVINE monster from your Deck to your hand. If Egyptian God Slime is on the field, it indirectly makes your entire field untargetable for card effects while making him a nearly undestructible monster that protects your monsters from being attacked. And since Slifer is also Level 10, not only it can be searched, but is also protected by the Field Spell. A Terraforming is added to the mix to either search it or search...
  • Lair of Darkness package: This Deck also features Ahrima, the Wicked Warden, Duke Shade, the Sinister Shadow & Lair of Darkness; where its intended use is for using the Torment Tokens as Tribute fodder. By this logic, both Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair & Lilith, Lady of Lament to use their effects in combination with Lair of Darkness. In the Side Deck, I added some of the Trap Cards it could be useful for this deck's playstyle that can be searched with Lilith's effect.
  • Millenium Revelation: Since I wanted to give a use to Guardian Slime's search effect, I added a copy of this card. Is a Continuous Spell that can send a Divine-Beast monster from the hand to the GY to add Monster Reborn from your Deck or GY to the hand. It also has another effect related to Ra's Summoning condition, but I mostly use it to search Monster Reborn.
  • Extra Deck: Pretty much anything you like. In my case, I added Synchro and Link monsters that could help to draw more cards, and a Halqifibrax as an extender; since this deck actually runs a Tuner, that being Scapeghost.
And that's for the Slifer version. The Obelisk version will be uploaded later today or tomorrow. Also, I would like to say that from now on, I'll try to post new recipes for the series every 2 weeks, on Fridays. This will give me time to playtest the decks and see which pros and cons each one has. Anyway, thanks for reading all this wall of text as always and I hope you like this kind of decks.

deck_name: Updated Dragon Link Post LCS 15 ( Jerome Weaver Inspired)
deck_description: Youtube link can be found in the comments!!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OKawk6-pnxc&t=81s The Strategy is fairly simple, break my opponent's board of interruptions/negates using a magical musket monster and magical musket hand traps in hand. The current meta ends on 2-4 negates and interruptions so with magical muskets all you need is a musket monster and cards on your opponent's side of the field to go off. Muskets strength is gaining an advantage from what your opponent gives you, so if they run a control deck you're going to be able to spam a bunch of Magical Musket monsters on the field, but if you're playing against a heavy combo deck you are going to be able to add all your Magical Musket hand traps to hand. My deck best matches up with heavy combo decks such as Xiangjian, Dinos, Heroes, Drytron, Cyber dragons, Infernobles and etc granted most of those decks run a good handful of hand traps so it'll ultimately come down to what you open with and how many handtraps your opponent opens up with turn 1. The approach I've given my deck is a going second because I main deck Dark Ruler No More, as well as Forbidden Droplets which is busted against the current meta and is amazing in Magical Muskets as Magical Musketeer Max, is your ace monster his effect says in short gain advantage by the number of cards you opponent controls on the field so you don't want to pop or remove your opponent's cards just negate the effects of their cards on their field.   Strengths: The strength of the deck is you can gain a fast advantage quickly depending on what your opponent is playing which can spiral into a huge advantage for you in the mid/late game.    Weaknesses: The biggest weaknesses the deck has are being able to see a musket monster in the starting turn and being able to successfully normal summon a musket monster to the field, which is why I run Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay and Pot of Prosperity to give the deck a little more draw power and consistency.   Side Deck: The list from my side was a major focus on the deck weakness explained above by mainly targetting kaiju's and anti-magic arrow as monsters on board and back row is the major problematic cards that Magical Musket monsters struggle with the on seeing you're normal summon. My handtraps in the side such as droll and ghost belle target the majority of the format on meta decks, so I decided to run them in the side vs main decking them as Dark Ruler No More and Forbidden Droplets are a 1 card instant combo for Magicial Muskets

deck_excerpt: Updated Solfachord deck for a post DAMA format.
deck_description:
"The enchanted conductrixes known as the 'Solfachord' troupe are well renowned the world over. Armed with plush familiars in their image and the mysterious powers of the pendulum, these musicians take to the stage. Recently, through a fan of theirs, they met with several performers and spellcasters who wanted to see if their talents can summon forth dragonic beings of the stars, the frozen depths and the very Vortex itself. Coolia, the leader and teacher of the troupe agreed to the collaboration, albeit with concern for the safety of her students. The ritual and concert was eventually interrupted when a data thief crashed it, the ensuing chaos caused a mysterious hero to arrive, seemingly from a world on the precipice of collapse... " Alright, with Dawn of Majesty set to arrive soon. I find it prudent to update the profile to v1 status now. Per the original profile, the aim is to have a semi-control deck that can consistently end on Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon and an enhanced Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. As such there are two new tools that I think could help with that:
  1. The first is Pendulum Xyz. A card that allows me to use the scales as Overlay Units, material for Xyz monster, and also allows one to be treated as the level of the other for the summon. As I run the Supreme King Package, this means I have a way to get Gate Zero used as material without Odd-Eyes Meteorburst Dragon, but the catch is that you will need new scales as a result. Duelist Alliance can also search this card and as such I opted to run a playset of that, and one of Pendulum Halt and Pendulum Call.
  2. The second is the upcoming archetypal Link monster: GranSolfachord Musecia. A link-2 monster that lets you add a Pendulum monster form the ED to the hand, replace that monster in the ED with another one (provided one is even and the other odd) and then search a Solfachord with a level that matches the scale of a Pendulum summoned monster.
The general strategy is still to try to get Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon and I:P Masquerena out, but the likely difference is that I would likely use Musecia as the first Link monster and then summon Masquerena later. What plays will ripple form those changes, and will these maestras used these tools for a crescendo?

deck_name: Tzolkin HEROes Deck Profile & Combo Guide August 2021
deck_excerpt: Here is a simple combo guide and deck profile for Tzolkin HEROes.
deck_description:
For those who have been playing since a decade ago, a variant of synchro HEROes have always existed; Destiny HERO – Zombies (2009), Diva HEROes, (2011), and Tzolkin HEROes (Since 2016) with the release of Ulitmaya Tzolkin. Despite A Hero Lives, Dark Grepher, Armageddon Knight, and Destiny HERO – Malicious being hit by the banlist, this deck is still going strong. Here is the updated version for August 2021. Combo 1 Starting Hand:
  • Elemental HERO Stratos
  • Fire Flint Lady
Ending Board:
  • Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon (x2)
  • Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon
  • Predaplant Verte Anaconda
  • Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade (Hand)
Steps:
  1. Normal summon Elemental HERO Stratos.
  2. Activate Elemental HERO Stratos to search Vision HERO Vyon.
  3. Special Summon Fire Flint Lady from the hand.
  4. Activate Fire Flint Lady to send itself to the graveyard and special summon Vision HERO Vyon from the hand.
  5. Activate Vision HERO Vyon to send Elemental HERO Shadow Mist from the deck to the graveyard.
  6. Activate Elemental HERO Shadow Mist to search Destiny HERO – Malicious.
  7. Activate Vision HERO Vyon 2nd effect to banish Elemental HERO Shadow Mist from the graveyard and search Polymerization.
  8. Link summon into Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights (Elemental HERO Stratos + Vision HERO Vyon) into the extra monster zone.
  9. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights to search Destiny HERO – Celestial. You will be setting up to use its draw effect in the future.
  10. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights 2nd to send 4 equip cards, including Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade, from the deck to the graveyard to special summon Dark Grepher from the deck.
  11. Activate Dark Grepher, send Destiny HERO – Malicious from the hand to the graveyard and then send Plaguespreader Zombie from the deck to the graveyard.
  12. Banish Destiny HERO – Malicious from the graveyard to special summon its copy from the deck.
  13. Activate Plaguespreader Zombie, return Destiny HERO – Celestial to the top of the deck to special summon itself from the graveyard.
  14. Synchro summon in Coral Dragon (Dark Grepher + Plaguespreader Zombie).
  15. Synchro summon into Ultimaya Tzolkin (Destiny HERO – Malicious + Coral Dragon).
  16. Activate Coral Dragon to draw 1 card which will be Destiny HERO – Celestial.
  17. Set Polymerization to activate Ultimaya Tzolkin and synchro summon Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon.
  18. Activate Polymerization to fusion summon into Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste (Ultimaya Tzolkin + Destiny HERO – Celestial).
  19. Activate Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste and banish Ultimaya Tzolkin to gain its effect.
  20. Activate Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade and banish 2 warriors from the graveyard to add it from the graveyard to the hand.
  21. Set Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade to activate Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste and synchro summon into the 2nd Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon.
  22. Activate Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade and equip it to Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights.
  23. Link summon into Predaplant Verte Anaconda (Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights + Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste). That will also send Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade to the graveyard.
  24. Activate Predaplant Verte Anaconda and copy Red-Eyes Fusion to fusion summon Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon (Dark Magician + Red-Eyes Black Dragon).
  25. Activate Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade and banish 2 warriors from the graveyard to add it from the graveyard to the hand. This will give you a card in your hand to discard for Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon.
Combo 2 Starting Hand:
  • Vision HERO Vyon
  • Fire Flint Lady
  • Miracle Synchro Fusion
Ending Board:
  • Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon (x2)
  • Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste
  • Destiny HERO - Dystopia
  • Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon
  • Predaplant Verte Anaconda
Steps:
  1. Normal summon Vision HERO Vyon.
  2. Activate Vision HERO Vyon to send Elemental HERO Shadow Mist from the deck to the graveyard.
  3. Activate Elemental HERO Shadow Mist to search Destiny HERO – Malicious.
  4. Activate Vision HERO Vyon 2nd effect to banish Elemental HERO Shadow Mist from the graveyard and search Polymerization.
  5. Special Summon Fire Flint Lady from the hand.
  6. Link summon into Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights (Vision HERO Vyon + Fire Flint Lady) into the extra monster zone.
  7. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights to search Destiny HERO – Celestial.
  8. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights 2nd to send 4 equip cards, including Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade, from the deck to the graveyard to special summon Armageddon Knight from the deck.
  9. Upon summon, activate Armageddon Knight and send Plaguespreader Zombie from the deck to the graveyard.
  10. Activate Polymerization to fusion summon Destiny HERO – Dystopia (Destiny HERO – Malicious + Destiny HERO – Celestial).
  11. Banish Destiny HERO – Malicious from the graveyard to special summon its copy from the deck.
  12. Activate Plaguespreader Zombie, return Miracle Synchro Fusion to the top of the deck to special summon itself from the graveyard.
  13. Synchro summon in Coral Dragon (Armageddon Knight + Plaguespreader Zombie).
  14. Synchro summon into Ultimaya Tzolkin (Destiny HERO – Malicious + Coral Dragon).
  15. Activate Coral Dragon to draw 1 card which will be Miracle Synchro Fusion.
  16. Set Miracle Synchro Summon to activate Ultimaya Tzolkin and synchro summon Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon.
  17. Link summon into Predaplant Verte Anaconda (Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights + Ultimaya Tzolkin) into the extra monster zone.
  18. Activate Miracle Synchro Fusion to fusion summon into Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste (Coral Dragon + Fire Flint Lady).
  19. Activate Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste and banish Ultimaya Tzolkin to gain its effect.
  20. Activate Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade and banish 2 warriors from the graveyard to add it from the graveyard to the hand.
  21. Set Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade to activate Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste and synchro summon into the 2nd Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon.

deck_excerpt: A deck featuring the "Vendread" archetype, a Zombie Ritual archetype that provides a solid mix of both beatdown and control strategies.
deck_description:
Here is my take at building a "Vendread" deck. "Vendread" is quite an interesting archetype since it features a Ritual monster theme with Zombie-Type monster, which is still a combination that no other archetype went for. If you heard of "Vendread" before, you might be aware of the fact that the hype around them died rather quickly when the powerful support was missing, leaving them in the limbo of semi-playability. Nonetheless, I think they are functional enough to build a deck around and they do have some aces to work with that might surprise the unaware opponent.

Starting with the monster line-up, I chose to include every "Vendread" Main Deck Effect monster except for "Vendread Core", since I did not need more Link material. That means one copy of "Vendread Revenants", which feature the worst revive effect but the absolutely insane Quick Effect banish when used as tribute for a "Vendread" Ritual monster. One copy of "Vendread Houndhorde" for the okayish revival and solid "Cosmic Cyclone" imitation effect for Rituals, one copy of "Vendread Striges", which features a very good revival effect but a subpar Ritual monster one, and one copy of "Vendread Anima" for added plays with banished monsters. "Vendread" does need some help from generic Zombies though, so I also included three "Gozuki" as "Foolish Burial" helpers, three "Uni-Zombie" for the same reason but they also work as Tuners for the deck, two "Shinobi Necro" as additional resources when banished for the Ritual Summon of a "Vendread" monster, one "Plaguespreader Zombie" as yet another Tuner and more material, one "Shiranui Solitaire" for potential "Uni-Zombie" setup, and three "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring" for the obvious handtrap effect, but also as a Zombie Tuner option for "Vendread".

The Ritual part of the deck is where it's at though, so I included both three "Preparation of Rites" and three "Pre-Preparation of Rites" as consistency tools, alongside three copies of "Revendread Origin" and three copies of "Revendread Evolution". To make the most out of "Preparation of Rites", you need to Ritual Summon first, then activate the card to make it a +1 in card economy terms. "Pre-Preparation of Rites" is always a +1, but comes with the caveat of only being able to search for the combination of "Revendread Slayer" and "Revendread Origin". Talking about "Revendread Slayer", he is in the deck at three copies but is also a pretty subpar Ritual monster on his own. However, by using the "Vendread" Main Deck Effect monsters as material you can give him some additional power and he is the easiest Ritual monster in the archetype to summon. "Vendread Battlelord" is the Level 7 Ritual and an absolute powerhouse in my opinion that can catch the opponent off-guard if they are not aware of what he does. You can easily summon him as the first action during your turn by ditching one copy of him from the deck via "Revendread Evolution" and then activate his effect to disallow the opponent from using monster effects, which in turn locks the opponent out of using handtraps and therefore gives you the opportunity to build your board in piece. I also included one copy of "Revendread Executor" for his protection effect, but he rarely saw play when I tested the deck. The rest of the Main Deck is made up by one "Foolish Burial" as graveyard setup and three copies of "Vendread Charge" to get your "Vendread" non-Ritual monsters on the field easier and to save resources from removal by dodging the effect in form of gaining another monster.

The Extra Deck has a lot of colorful options, since "Vendread" on its own really does not need that much of the space in there. Both "Shiranui Sunsaga" and "Shiranui Shogunsaga" work as beatsticks, "Borreload Savage Dragon" can equip Link monsters for negates and is fairly easy to make, "Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon" is a situational option with battle focus, "Black Rose Dragon" serves as the usual field nuke, "Herald of the Arc Light" can work as a negation tool as well as searching for Ritual cards, "Formula Synchron" can be summoned via "Crystron Halqifibrax" which itself provides more resources, "Knightmare Phoenix" is the usual backrow removal option, "Vampire Sucker" can have merit in some situations, "Avendread Savior" is the only archetypal Extra Deck monster and can recycle resources, provides graveyard setup and can even potentially run some opposing monster over, "Abyss Dweller" is the counter option against another graveyard-heavy deck and "Evilswarm Exciton Knight" is more of an emergency tool if you cannot manage to make something more useful and want to potentially stop the opponent from going crazy with summons.

"Vendread" has some interesting interactions and is quite a deckbuilding challenge; however, they do have a small number of dedicated players that experiment with various options, like using "Spirit Sculptor" in order to search for other helpful engine parts. The deck provides a number of effects that can surprise the opponent that did not read the cards, since "Vendread" Main Deck monsters tend to revive themselves, the "Vendread" Ritual monster provide searches upon their demise, "Vendread Battlelord" disabling entire card types and the Ritual Spell "Revendread Origin" serving as protection for some of the archetypal monsters while in the graveyard. Granted, you will find better (Zombie) decks if you look for them, but "Vendread" is not that bad and certainly unique enough to give them a spin; and if you are really interested, you might want to check out my archetype analysis on them, which you can find here: https://cubiccreativity.wordpress.com/2021/08/07/archetype-analysis-vendread/

deck_excerpt: A deck using the card "Fire Princess", which damages the opponent whenever you are healed. The strategy is also known as "Cure Burn".
deck_description:
This is my take at building a "Fire Princess Burn" deck, which is also referred to as "Cure Burn". The main card to use in this strategy is obviously "Fire Princess", a Level 4 monster that inflicts 500 damage to the opponent whenever you gain life points. This means that you normally need sixteen ticks of healing with "Fire Princess" around to inflict lethal damage to the opponent, which is certainly a more casual-oriented strategy to use, but one that can be fun to work with. But due to the age of the strategy, there are various older cards that do not necessarily see play anymore in other decks.

The monsters are quite simple: We use three copies of "UFO Turtle" as the searcher to fetch us one of the three copies of "Fire Princess". Granted, "UFO Turtle" is a battle searcher and the entire idea of battle searchers rotated out of the interest of players a few years ago, but it certainly helps via blocking attacks, searching the necessary monster and keeps the deck very budget-friendly even for a casual deck. The last triplet comes in form of three copies of "Golden Ladybug", which passively heals during the Standby Phase and therefore gives us a slow but recurring trigger for the effect of "Fire Princess".

There are quite a few more Spell cards to talk about, since three copies of "Spell Absorption" can make quite the difference in the game by spamming this card type. Three "Ancient Leaf" can trigger "Spell Absorption" while also making use of the added life points for more draw power, three "Goblin Thief" are a dream card to use with "Fire Princess" due to supporting both the burn strategy via healing as well as inflicting damage on its own, three "Ledger of Legerdemain" can fetch more of the necessary cards via draw and the deck is able to stall enough to make that work, three "Swords of Revealing Light" are further stall options and also give a "Spell Absorption" trigger, two "Child's Play" help protecting "Fire Princess" while providing more healing for the "Cure Burn" strategy, three "Cauldron of the Old Man" provide constant healing/burning, three copies of "Dark Sanctuary" provide further protection while also inflicting damage, one "Terraforming" serves as a fourth draw for "Dark Sanctuary", one "Poison of the Old Man" serves as more healing/burning, one "Mystical Space Typhoon" against pesky backrow and one copy of "Magical Mallet" to shuffle unnecessary cards away while also providing another "Spell Absorption" tick.

The Trap cards are fairly straightforward: Two copies of "Bye Bye Damage" can kill the careless opponent when running one of your monsters over, while two copies of "Wall of Disruption" can lower them far enough to be a non-threat to your health points and for them to take additional damage due to running into a higher ATK monster. The Extra Deck is only really filled with options that could be potentially made, with cards like "Castel the Skyblaster Musketeer" to work against opposing monsters that block your strategy, while "Gagaga Cowboy" can be used to inflict another 800 damage and therefore potentially finishing a few games.

"Cure Burn" is nowhere near powerful enough to keep up with many decks in the modern meta. However, it is a fun little strategy for casual if you are searching for a deck that does not use an archetype to run. If you are interested in the deck and want to read more about it, feel free to visit the article about it on my blog here: https://cubiccreativity.wordpress.com/2021/01/09/archetype-analysis-fire-princess-burn/
Just have fun with it.

deck_excerpt: Archfiends and the Unchained team up to destroy everything!
deck_description: Deck profile, guide and combos here Hi everyone, The Archfiend Guy here again, this time with a more competitive focus on Archfiends! The core of the deck is still the same, summon Archfiend Empress and float with her effect and the Dark Spirit monsters, only this time we are combining them with an Unchained engine. Unchained cards, such as Unchained Twins - Aruha and Abominable Chamber of the Unchained, are in this deck to boost the early game power by setting up Unchained Soul of Rage interruptions, whilst also providing some nice destruction synergy. Deck playstyle: Beatdown Core cards: Archfiend Emperor, Archfiend Empress, Dark Spirit of Malice, Dark Spirit of Banishment Gameplay: You want to dump your fiends into the grave as soon as possible so that you can revive them from there later. You mainly summon during the opponent's turn to pressure them into outing your monsters, which depletes their resources whilst also providing you with a fairly powerful wall. Archfiend Empress in combination with a Dark Spirit is a decent loop of protection! In addition to that, you have access to the fairly unique method of removal via the Unchained cards. Unchained Soul of Rage and Unchained Soul of Disaster provide removal through using your opponent's monsters as material for link summons! Also, monsters such as Knightmare Unicorn provide more interruptions Masterking Archfiend is a great card that can give you access to additional Archfiend Heiress searches, and has a maintenance cost! This means you can choose to remove it, which is useful if your opponent is using that pesky Mystic Mine...

deck_excerpt: Going first version of the Sunrise HERO Deck
deck_description: The idea of the deck is to end on Elemental HERO Sunrise and Masked HERO Dark Law turn 1 as consistently as possible while adding to your hand Miracle Fusion and Dark Calling in the Process. deck_excerpt: A going 2nd variant of Sunrise HEROs
deck_description: Going second gives you the ability to clear your opponent’s field with large board wipes and establish a field very easily afterwards or to just OTK then and there. Personally, I have also dropped Dynatag now and don’t miss him.

This is my current personal favourite build of HEROs. Going first to set up Dark Law is crucial in the current metagame. The addition of Pot of Prosperity allows you to deep draw into your deck after your combo so you can try and find any last missing piece like Mask Change or Elemental HERO Honest Neos.

If you’ve not got the budget to stretch to cards like Lightning Storm and the Evil HERO Package, then this build is for you. It still maintains a degree of competitiveness while being more affordable. The aim is to still end on Masked HERO Dark Law and Elemental HERO Sunrise as quickly as possible then only drawback is that there is not as much recovery from field wipes like Nibiru, The Primal Being.

deck_excerpt: A predominantly Swordsoul strategy splashed with a D/D engine to add extra combo plays and dig deeper into the synchro pool.
deck_description: Swordsoul is a crazy new Synchro archetype that is very consistent. Your main starter is either going to be Mo Ye, as he can one-card synchro into Chi Xiao which gives you a search AND Mo Ye draws you a card on synchro summon, or Eccclesia, who can tribute herself to special summon Mo Ye, and start your combos from there.  The D/D engine is in here to go into Halqifibrax plays and to dig deeper into the synchro pool, however, it's not as consistent as just the Swordsoul engine is. When it goes off, you can end on some devastating boards, but if you prefer to use a pure Swordsoul engine, the side deck is catered to taking out the D/D engine, and just using generic handtraps and removal.     There Can Be Only One is a great tech option for games two and three, as your ideal end board will have no more than one type of monster on the field, and can completely shut down monotype archetypes you may be facing.

deck_name: Sacred Eldlich - A Far Away Dream
deck_excerpt: Sacred Beast Hamon and Eldlich The Golden Lord go to battle together!
deck_description:
Hello there, this is a deck I have been working on recently. The deck is build out of two engines: 1. Sacred Beast part:
  • This engine is there to put big boys with protection on the board. I did choose Hamon since it is the best standalone monster out of the trio. Also, its support card Cerulean Skyfire is searchable with Curious and adds a nice interruption to your end board.
  • Opening of the Spirit Gates is the strongest card of the engine. It searches every other peace you are are missing (except for Skyfire). It recycles Cerulean Skyfire AND even Cursed Eldland if needed. And it also helps to make combo plays. 
  • Fallen Paradise delivers the needed protection for your Hamon. It also generates a +2 every turn, if not dealt with by your opponent.
2. Eldlich part:
  • This part is here for the grind game.
  • Eldlich the golden Lord is central for the engine to work and delivers in addition a level 10 body with whom you can go into either Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max or Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos.
  • Most of the trap cards can be used as cost for other parts of the deck and can float out of the graveyard.
Notable Generics:
  • Magician's Souls is a broken card which can draw you two cards and by the way get your Eldlich engine rolin'.
  • Exodius the Ultimate forbidden Lord is the target for Souls, can be a level 10 body for Link or Xyz plays and helps to recycle your monster cards.  
The deck has problems going second and is overall not perfect, but I like the synergy between the two archetypes. I would love to own this deck IRL, but a lot of cards are very expensive, so it won't happen in a foreseeable future... The side deck presents some accountable options, but can be customized at will. Suggestions to improve the deck are welcome. :) Have a nice day, everyone!

deck_excerpt: A take on the Magistus strategy that aims to consistently end boards on Zoroa thru multiple hand traps.
deck_description: First time posting a list on here, here goes.  Description:  Magistus has been a deck that has been out since Genesis Impact. Taken to be the worst deck of the set (and rightfully so), it has yet to make a impact on the meta. With the introduction of Zoroa, The Magistus Daimon to the deck in BODE, the archetype has finally gained a good consistent 1st turn board. The goal of course, is to end on Zoroa with multiple equips attached to lock the opponent out of the game. Then on the next turn, set up negates or end the game with Accesscode.  Let's go through the list together:  Magistus Engine: x20  3 Verre: This card is our S/T searcher for the deck. (Also has an effect to bring down material from the banish zone). Verre allows us to grab our extenders and is one of the best cards to grab off Artemis for the next turn play (that being if you already have a way to end on Zoroa). Also has a banish effect to equip more Magistus cards from GY (important for more ED locking and/or extension plays).  3 Zoroa: The tuner of the deck. Drawing him allows you to go into Zoroa under 5 summons or Borreload Savage early on. Typically your revive target off of Vitra but a necessary card of the combo.  Can also serve as a proper starter by attaching Artemis and grabbing a needed card.  3x Endymion: The more barebones starter of the deck. Does everything that you would want from it. Typically, you'll be attaching Artemis to start off your plays and/or Ninanruru/Rilliona to play thru the opp board. It's also a decent hand fixer.  3x Crowley: Our extender of the deck. Does nothing by itself but is important to have as it serves as one of the main ways you'll get to Zoroa.  Also has the same effect as Verre.  3x Vitra: Our monster reborn for the archetype. A card that you'll be grabbing off of Rilliona on the follow-up turn or an extender to end on your intended board. Also has a Magistus equipped protection effect that is important for keeping the lock in place.  3x Trismagistus: One of the best cards in the archetype. Serves as a soul charge from the hand and another way to extend your plays. Also has a nice battle protection effect for magistus cards equipped with an extra deck card. Really good card.  2x Theurgy: One of the most "cuttable" parts of the list. It serves as another way to attach Artemis or play thru opponents boards. Especially important in a meta with effect veiler/imper as it allows our cards to still get to full combo thru interruption. Also serves as a type of interruption on the opp turn by attaching an extra ED monster to your magistus monsters.  Starters:  Rilliona, Zoroa, Endymion  Extenders:  Crowley, Trismagistus, Vitra, Theurgy  More "Generic Cards": x8  2x Spell Power Mastery. A useful card that allows us to search for Endymion. This card allows us to get to our starter even if we don't draw it. Ran only at 2 because we really don't want to draw more then one.  1x Called by the grave: Pretty self-explanatory. Allows you to negate a handtrap or serves as a interruption on opp turn.  2x Cosmic Cyclone: Flex spot of the deck but it's always nice to have more S/T removal.  3x Triple Tactics Talent: This card can easily be switched for Desires. Due to the nature of this deck being able to combo with basically any two card hand, TTT serves as more of another extender drawer or board breaker for going second.  Hand-Traps: (What - we're playing YGO in 2021 aren't we?) x12  3x Ash Blossom  3x Effect Veiler  3x Droll & Lock Bird  3x Infinite Impermanence  Standard selection of HTs. It's important to recognize that Effect Veiler and Droll are both spellcasters. Meaning that they can link into Artemis to start plays or be discard fodder for Crowley.  Extra deck:  2x Artemis - the best equip card that the deck has. It allows the search for any of our Magistus monsters that we need in hand.  1x Ninanruru - Our S/T removal other then cosmic. Can be useful to force activation of cards. Also has a nifty effect to allow two attacks on monsters.  1x Vahram - The main target to equip to Zoroa. Gives Zoroa a construct-like send and S/T protection. Also has a boardwipe effect that burns all face-up cards. Just like the fiery bird it is.  1x Aiwass - Our target for Fusion matchups. Can also be made with Invocation in matchups that don't use the ED. Don't forget the atk/def gain effect to hit over monsters.  2x Rilliona - Typically the card that allows the search for baby Zoroa. Allows us to consistently go into Zoroa. Remember that this card locks us into Magistus ED monsters. Also has a neat effect to negate a monster on your turn.  1x Zoroa, the Magistus of Daimon - Our main t1 board usually revolves around him. Important to realize that Zoroa says the cards don't have to be attached to him to do the floodgate effect and that Zoroa works no matter where the ED monster attempts to activate. Also has a neat reincarnation effect that becomes useful for plays later on and to reestablish the lock. Can be ran at 1 or 2 - up to your preference.  1x Borrel Savage - Omni negate that can be made t1 to play around Nibiru if you have full combo or be made in matchups that don't use the ED. Also a neat target on later turns for more negation.  1x Bahmaut Shark/1x Toadally Awesome - fans of this deck already knows about these cards. You typically make this with Endmyion and Crowley (by changing Crowley to water). Another play to play around Nibiru or to have another negation on the board.  1x Halq/Selene/Accesscode - Standard Accesscode link climb combo. Make Halq with Zoroa and another monster then SS Veiler. Then link into Selene and revive another spellcaster. Then go into Accesscode. Typically the play that you will do to end the game.  1x Dragite - Honestly, this is the flex spot of the deck. Choose whatever you would like to run in this spot. Running Dragite just for another S/T negation when I can't get a link in GY for Savage. Pick whatever  you would like for this spot.  Side Deck:  Meta dependent but to explain choices:  1x Magistus Invocation - Now you might be asking, why are you running this card in the side? Well, to be honest typically you won't be ending on Aiwass with Invocation in the deck as you would have to search invocation off Rilliona. The problem with that is that if you have the search for Rilliona, typically you'll be looking to grab ways to break boards or extend. The card itself serves as a brick in the starting hand and does nothing for us in the way for extension. In testing this deck, I rarely grabbed this card and loathed the times it was in my starting hand.  3x Secret Village - We're a spellcaster deck so might as well run one of our good support cards. This card + Zoroa can often lead to unbreakable boards. Good for locking your opp out of Spell cards.  1x Cosmic - to finish off the 2 in the MD  1x Feather Duster - Good S/T wipe card.  Of course, change what you would like in the SD. All up to the players preference.  Finale: As explained earlier, most 2 cards in the deck lead to ending on Zoroa. That means that you will be able to consistently end on the ED lock. This list intends to end on that board thru multiple disruption.  Basic Combo with Rilliona and any other Magistus Spellcaster:  NS Rilliona -> grab Trismagistus -> Activate Tris -> SS Spellcaster -> XYZ into Rilliona -> Activate Rilliona (Detach Rilliona Spellcaster) SS Zoroa -> Zoroa Effect Attach anything (Typically something you don't want to equip with Zoroa T1 like Ninanruru (or if you don't want to lock out Links something you do want to attach) -> Zoroa effect to revive -> Syncro into Daimon -> Effect Daimon to attach -> Rilliona GY effect to attach to Magistus monster  (Typically you'll attach the Link to the Rilliona XYZ. Reasoning being that Tris will give Rilliona one BP protection now and you'll force your opp to deal with both Zoroa and Rilliona or else you'll get value on the following turn off both Artemis and XYZ).  Of course, this is one of the many combos that lead to full combo. This deck doesn't really have one exact play to establish the lock (thou it'll typically involve the XYZ).  Strengths:  Consistent - most two card hands get to combo (more so if you have a starter)  Can play thru multiple disruption.  Can outright win some games.  Weaknesses:  Nibiru (If you don't get to a negate before Nibiru (which some hands can - make sure to think out your plays!))  Board Breaker cards like DRNM.  Decks that focus on Main Deck monsters.  Anyways, that wraps up this post. Feel free to comment suggestions! This deck has many different variations, so any tips is appreciated! Thank you for reading my post and have a nice day.  (There's also a discord server for Magistus on which I'm pretty active! Feel free to join!)
